\par\par \b \uc2  Foreign investors seeking more stable environment. \b0\par\par\uc2 476 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 April 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Eun-ho Seung, Chairman of Korean Chamber of Commerce in Indonesia \par \par \uc2  Fundamentally, the country remains an attractive place for investments thanks to its abundant natural resources, huge potential market and large pool of labor. \par \par \uc2  But it will likely take a few more years more before new foreign investors will return to Indonesia, due to a combination of domestic problems, weak economies in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) region and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition. \par \par \uc2  Most foreign investors now prefer to wait and see due to weak law enforcement, overly rigid labor regulations and other problems inherent to the current transition to a more democratic and decentralized system of government, as well as the simmering political climate in the run up to the 2004 general election. However, if the new government that takes office in late 2004 is able to improve the general climate for business and strengthen political and social stability, foreign investors may return sooner than expected. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia is now less attractive to new investors than China and Vietnam and it needs to learn from these countries about how they designed their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, legal framework and labor and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  regulations to woo investment. Many have complained about the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by the decentralization of power to the regions, although decentralization is a rational choice for this vast archipelagic country. \par \par \uc2  What matters to investors is that this process should not cause new problems, such as unclear division of authority between the central government and local administrations, \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  inconsistencies, arduous licensing procedures and double \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  burdens. Such problems not only increase the costs of doing business but, most damagingly, fuel the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that is the number one enemy to investors. \par \par \uc2  Suffocating labor regulations and the tendency for militant trade unions are especially inimical to Korean business operations in Indonesia because most Korean investors operate in labor-intensive industries. They depend on peaceful industrial relations and a consistent wage \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  There are now 570 Korean companies operating in Indonesia with total investment of US$9.5 billion. They manufacture a wide range of industrial products such as shoes, textile and garments, bags and stuffed toys and various other light industrial goods. They employ around 500,000 workers, with annual exports of about $4.5 billion of various manufactured products. Korean investment operations have also contributed greatly to expanding bilateral trade to more than US$7.8 billion annually. \par \par \uc2  The ASEAN Free Trade Area theoretically makes Indonesia, by far the largest member of the regional grouping, much more attractive to investors as they can use the country as a beachhead to export to other ASEAN countries under the preferential \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  arrangements. \par \par \uc2  Before that happens, however, investors need more stable political, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social conditions to enable them to reasonably calculate their business risks. \par \par \uc2  - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 30 - - - - - - \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030425dz