\par\par \b \uc2  Govt expects higher growth. \b0\par\par\uc2 647 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Dadan Wijaksana, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Minister of Finance Boediono projected higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth for next year on the back of improvements in investment and exports, provided the upcoming 2004 \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections runs smoothly. \par \par \uc2  Boediono, speaking during preliminary discussions of the draft 2004 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  in front of the House of Representative's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  commission, said the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow between 4 percent to 5 percent next year. \par \par \uc2  "If the 2004 election goes well ... I think by the second semester of the year, foreign investment will return," he said. \par \par \uc2  This target is higher than projections made by the World Bank and Asian Development Bank who predicted 4 percent growth. \par \par \uc2  The two multilateral lenders also disagree with the government's 2003 growth target of 4 percent, saying the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would only expand by 3.3 percent to 3.4 percent, down from 3.7 percent last year, thus worsening the unemployment situation. \par \par \uc2  Boediono conceded that even with 4 percent to 5 percent growth in 2004, it would not be able to resolve the severe unemployment problems. He said that the government had to be realistic in setting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  targets. \par \par \uc2  The country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  contracted by more than 13 percent in 1998 following the regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. Since the crisis, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has only managed to grow at a meager rate of around 3 percent per year. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have said that to resolve unemployment problems, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must grow at a pre-crisis rate of around 6 percent. \par \par \uc2  Boediono said global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions were expected to improve next year, thus providing opportunities for the country to increase exports and lure more investment. \par \par \uc2  Over the years, investment has been hard to come by because of internal and external factors, contributing little to the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, which has been mainly relying on strong domestic consumption. \par \par \uc2  The current global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, exacerbated by the recent Iraq war and the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS), has shattered investors' confidence worldwide, putting a lid on their appetites to invest in emerging markets, such as Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  On top of that, however, it is the adverse investment climate here, partly due to security concerns and rampant corruption, that have discouraged the flow of capital into the country. \par \par \uc2  Security will be more of a concern when the election process begins next year. Traditionally, tensions rise whenever elections takes place due to increased political friction. \par \par \uc2  However, Boediono remained optimistic on the prospects for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , despite the various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Even under the current conditions, take exports for example, some of our commodities are enjoying good bargains, in terms of the prices. \par \par \uc2  "Oil is an obvious example, and so are some agricultural and mining products. So, there is no need to be pessimistic. Our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be better in 2004 as investment and exports improve," he said. \par \par \uc2  The state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 2004 was earmarked at 1 percent of gross domestic product, lower than this year's target of 1.8 percent. \par \par \uc2  But Boediono did not provide specific details on how to plug the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  considering that the country may no longer be able to obtain debt rescheduling facilities from the Paris Club next year if the existing International Monetary Fund (IMF) program is terminated later this year as scheduled. \par \par \uc2  He said the government would optimize potential revenue from both domestic sources, including divestment and privatization, and foreign ones, which included seeking further soft-term loans from the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) and debt-swaps with other creditor nations. \par \par \uc2  Govt \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  targets \par \par \uc2  - \par \par \uc2  2003 2004 * - Inflation (%) 9 7 - 8 Rupiah per US$ 9,000 8,500 - 9,500 GDP growth (%) 4 4 - 5 Oil Price (US$/barrel) 22 17 - 20 Oil Output (bpd) 1.27m 1.1m - 1.5m SBI (%) 13 10.5 - 11.5 \b \highlight22\uc2 Deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  (% of GDP) 1.8 1 - * preliminary assumption Source: Ministry of Finance \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030501dz510005m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
