\par\par \b \uc2  Part 2 of 2 IMF inhibiting RI's improvement, inflating inequity. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,290 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  7 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Rizal Ramli, Former Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Reform of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system is necessary to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  autonomy and reduce dependence on foreign borrowing. It is time for groups that have benefited from 35 years of New Order government to share in the burden of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform would increase revenues and make it possible to both use \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to accelerate the recovery and reduce structural inequality. Recommended measures include, among others: \par \par \uc2  1. Increasing the number of Indonesians on the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  roll. \par \par \uc2  In November 2000, two million people were listed on the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  roll. Using a range of devices, including inspections at elite housing estates, the number of taxpayers was increased to 2.9 million in less than seven months. It is estimated that potential taxpayers under the current law could number as many as five million people. \par \par \uc2  2. Reducing nominal income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  but increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  effectiveness. \par \par \uc2  The nominal rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia is 30 percent. In other ASEAN countries rates vary between 22 percent and 25 percent. Indonesia would be more attractive to investors if nominal rates were reduced. Until now, although nominal rates are as high as 30 percent, in practice, negotiations take place between the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities and taxpayers that reduce the effective \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate to around 10 percent. Therefore, any move to reduce the nominal rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be accompanied by measures to improve \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection. \par \par \uc2  3. Introducing a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty \par \par \uc2  The introduction of a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty would enable corporations and individuals that have evaded \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the past to come into compliance with \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws. \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evaders would, of course, have to pay a penalty and back \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The two main advantages of introducing provisions for a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty are: first, increased revenues from back \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and penalties; second, an increase in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  base in future years. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesties are only effective if accompanied by strict enforcement of the law as a means of reducing the scope for \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evasion in future years. In the absence of rigorous enforcement of existing laws, the possibility of a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty would not attract evaders and the measures would therefore be a waste of time. \par \par \uc2  These efforts, taken together, have the potential to raise an additional Rp 90 trillion in revenue over the next three years (2003 to 2005). \par \par \uc2  The government must make better use of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  funds. For example, the government maintains a number of special accounts containing funds that are rarely reported to the legislature and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . These accumulated funds must be put to work for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefit. The amounts contained in these accounts are sufficient to ease the government's cash flow problems in the short term. Account 69 (formerly Account 16) is an account set up by the New Order for off-\b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The funds in this account were derived from the difference between actual oil prices and the price set in the government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the year. \par \par \uc2  At the moment Account No. 69 contains Rp. 18 trillion. Similarly, the government accumulates undisbursed funds from the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and funds in the Investment Fund Account derived from the interest rate difference between the government's overseas borrowing and second-tier lending at higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to banks or state-owned companies. At the moment, the Investment Fund Account contains Rp. 2l trillion. These resources should be put to work in the form of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  investment to accelerate the recovery. \par \par \uc2  The government must reach a fair and viable agreement with \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) over BI's role in the Liquidity Credit (BLBI) scandal. The BPK audit of BLBI concluded that BI bore responsibility for the misuse of Rp 84.8 trillion, from a total of Rp 144.5 trillion in liquidity credits supplied from the beginning of the crisis until Jan. 29, 1999. \par \par \uc2  The oil and gas sector has great potential to stimulate Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. Optimization of income from this sector would generate substantial funds for national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. It is probable that Indonesia will experience a natural gas boom over the coming decade. \par \par \uc2  The management of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt will play a key role in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the post-IMF period. Dependence on the IMF and the Paris Club would be greatly reduced if the government could reduce its stock of debt and the burden of debt servicing on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Unfortunately, the current pro-IMF \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  regime adheres to a dogmatic approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  finance. \par \par \uc2  The current focus is on shifting around and adding to the debt burden, rather than reducing it. This approach results in a counterproductive \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that restrains rather than promotes growth. \par \par \uc2  Regarding domestic debt, the approach of the current government can be described as "triple R": Rollover, reprofiling and refinancing. The aim of reprofiling is to change the maturities of existing bonds. Refinancing depends entirely on the resilience, liquidity and confidence of the domestic bond market. \par \par \uc2  This means that the government depends entirely on refinancing. If, for example, 75 percent of the principal of recap bonds falling due over a given year were refinanced, then the value of new bonds would vary from Rp 4.7 trillion to Rp 28.3 trillion per year from 2003 to 2018. The question is whether the domestic bond market is resilient and liquid enough to absorb these new bond issues. \par \par \uc2  In 2004, Indonesia will hold the first direct presidential elections in the country's history. This will be a year of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  risk, political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , social tension and security concerns. Under this scenario, Indonesia must issue bonds valued at Rp 19.1 trillion in the same year within the context of a contractionary \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  stance. Would the market be willing to absorb the new bonds under these conditions? In other words, this triple-R strategy carries a high risk of default, and binds Indonesia ever more tightly to the IMF. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's debt management strategy must therefore be oriented toward the reduction of debt stocks. The independent team on bank recap bonds identified five alternative solutions to the problem of domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt: Asset-to-bond swaps (AB swaps); adjustments to capital adequacy ratio (CAR), interest-bearing perpetual bonds (IBPB) and bond pooling. \par \par \uc2  If one of these proposals, or perhaps a combination or adaptation of several were to be adopted, the reduction of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt servicing would be substantial. For example, if the proposal for indirect acquisition among recap banks were adopted and accompanied by interest-bearing perpetual bonds, then Rp 27.6 trillion in recap bonds could be withdrawn and Rp 3.59 trillion in interest payments would be saved (at an SBI (\b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Certificate) rate of 13 percent). With the issuance of IBPBs, principal payments of Rp 11.6 billion would be eliminated. Total savings would be at least Rp 15.2 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Another idea would be to trade shares in state-owned companies for recap bonds held by state-owned recap banks (bonds-to-share swaps) and swaps of infrastructure-related foreign debt (for example, debts of state electricity company PLN) for recap bonds. \par \par \uc2  Releasing our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from the confines of an IMF agreement will help, but it is not in itself a solution to Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems. \par \par \uc2  We must work hard to attack the three main obstacles to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery: political instability, the lack of secure rights to property and personal safety, and the absence of the rule of law. Even the most carefully constructed \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  program cannot overcome the negative effects of these essentially political and social constraints to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress. This will require leadership and vision, two elements distinctly lacking in the current administration. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030501dz510005z\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  March's Export Volume Exceeds US$5 Billion. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,018 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 May 2003\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Indonesia's export volume in March 2003 reached US$5.07 billion, or the highest over the past 18 months. \par \par \uc2  Slamet Mukeno, Deputy of Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Statistics said the export performance in March increased 3.85% compared to February. \par \par \uc2  "In the same period, import decreased by 2.53% to US$2.88 billion," he said in Jakarta yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Based on Bisnis' calculation, the development created US$2.19 billion in trade surplus in March or higher compared to February's US$1.92 billion. \par \par \uc2  Slamet revealed in March the import volume declined by 2.53% compared to February. \par \par \uc2  He explained the export growth in 2003 was in line with the global upsurge trend of the world trade in the month. \par \par \uc2  "The export in March rose by 3.85% compared to February. This is in line with the global upsurge trend in March, so that the export volume for the first time this year can exceed US$5 billion level," Slamet said. \par \par \uc2  Data by BPS also showed the last time the export performance figure exceeded US$5 billion level, which was US$5.14 billion, happened in August 2001. \par \par \uc2  Data by BPS also disclosed that cumulatively the export volume in the first three months of 2003 reached US$14.87 billion or rose by 15.83% compared to US$12.84 billion the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  The improvement was motivated by the performance of non-oil and gas export that rose by 5.29% from US$3.62 billion in March to US$3.81 billion in March, so that the non-oil and gas export in January-March 2003 reached US$11.16 billion or grew by 9.74% compared to the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, oil and gas export declined by 0.27% in March from US$1.257 billion to US$1.254 billion, which was triggered by the declining natural gas export volume that only touched US$539 million. Whereas crude oil export still grew to US$535 million. \par \par \uc2  "The increasing crude oil export volume is caused by the rocketing export volume, while the crude oil price in the world market actually decreases from US$32.04 per barrel in February to US$30.36 per barrel in March 2003," said Slamet. \par \par \uc2  Import Declined \par \par \uc2  Separately, the import in March 2003 declined by 2.53% from US$2.96 billion in February to US$2.88 billion. However, cumulatively the import in the first three months of this year rose by 29.4% to US$8.58 billion from US$6.63 billion in the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  The declining import volume in March was caused by the non-oil and gas import that declined by 2.17% to US$2.28 billion, while in January-March 2003 the non-oil and gas import grew by 27.42% to US$6.64 billion. \par \par \uc2  Chief subdivision of BPS for Export, Dantes Simbolon, explained the trend of the weakening domestic consumption, and also the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition and the gloomy prospect of the labor pool, were crucial factors that pressed down the import performance. \par \par \uc2  "The contribution of the consumption and capital good imports in the import are also decreasing by 8.43% and 11.36%." \par \par \uc2  Simbolon added that the US was still the major destination country for the non-oil and gas export. However, the contribution to the total non-oil and gas export volume in January-March 2003 declined from 18% in January-March the previous year to 14.6% this year. \par \par \uc2  After the US, Japan is the second target country of Indonesia's non-oil and gas export, which represented 14.26% of the export, followed by Singapore that represented 10.42%. Meanwhile, China, which is predicted to become 'another major target country for Indonesia' only represented 5.1% of the total non-oil and gas export. \par \par \uc2  "The non-oil and gas export share to the US usually is fixed at around 18%. But, now the figure hovers at 14%. This is probably caused by the political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown in the countries." \par \par \uc2  Commodities that have shown improvement are CPO, copper, rubber and rubber-made products, wood, paper. Whereas the once top commodities of garments and socks declined last month. \par \par \uc2  Inflation at 15% \par \par \uc2  The rising prices of processed food, beverages, cigarettes, and tobaccos boosted 0.15% inflation rate higher in April 2003, or declined from February that enjoyed the deflation rate of 0.23%. In the same month last year, the inflation rate was at 7.54%. \par \par \uc2  The development boosted the inflation rate in the four first months this year to 0.92%. According to BPS, the price movement to April 2003 was still tolerable for the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  that assumed the inflation rate at 9% this year. \par \par \uc2  Slamet said the increasing sugar price had only contributed relatively small percentage, which was only 0.16% since the consumption of sugar was low, to the price movement throughout April 2003. \par \par \uc2  "The rising sugar price only contributed 0.16% of April's inflation rate of 0.15%. Although sugar is important, the people's sugar consumption rate was relatively low at 0.2-0.3%. Tasikmalaya people are the ones consume the sugar least, while Surakarta people are the ones consume the sugar most. \par \par \uc2  Inflation happened because the rising prices of processed food, beverages, cigarette, and tobacco; properties, health-care; education, recreation, and sport; and transportation and communication, which grew by 1.41%, 0.6%, 0.32%, and 0.27%, 1.31%, respectively. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the food and garment sectors suffered declining prices by 1.15% and 0.64%, respectively, in April 2003. \par \par \uc2  The processed food, beverages, cigarette, and tobacco; properties, health-care; education, recreation, and sport; and the food and garment sectors contributed 0.28%, 0.04%, 0.01%, 0.03%, and 0.06%, respectively, to the inflation rate. \par \par \uc2  Goods and services that increased in price in April 2003 were, among other things, white sugar, purebred chicken meat, orange, local transportation, home servant wages, house rent, prescribed medication, and school. (07). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020030502dz520005l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
