\par\par \b \uc2  RI media yet to enjoy press freedom. \b0\par\par\uc2 506 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Muninggar Sri Saraswati, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Most media in the country have yet to enjoy freedom of the press following the downfall of the repressive New Order regime in 1998 due to a number of factors, including \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  constraints. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the Indonesian Newspaper Publishers Association Leo Batubara revealed on Friday that only 30 percent of 596 print media in the country were considered "healthy" and profitable. \par \par \uc2  Of the electronic media, only 10 percent of 1,100 radio stations and three of 20 television stations were healthy. \par \par \uc2  "This situation has forced those unfortunate media, particularly tabloids, to produce sensational and bombastic publications to raise their circulation," he said on Friday. \par \par \uc2  As many media still struggled to survive, Leo added, they could not make use of the freedom they had to monitor the performance of the government, the legislature and the judiciary. \par \par \uc2  Hordes of new investors have entered the media industry following the abolition of licensing requirements by the government under former president B. J. Habibie, and the liquidation of the Ministry of Information, which practically controlled the media, by then president Abdurrahman Wahid. \par \par \uc2  However, the situation has been abused by corrupt businesspeople and politicians, who have bought media companies in order to control \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion. \par \par \uc2  In addition to control by businesspeople, the media also faced another huge challenge: to free itself from the threat of mob violence. \par \par \uc2  Citing the recent attack by sympathizers of businessman Tomy Winata on Tempo magazine's offices, Leo also said that currently, the media had to deal with mob violence. \par \par \uc2  Chief editor of Tempo Bambang Harymurti said that growing violence against the media served as a setback for press freedom in the country. \par \par \uc2  "I think it has happened due to legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  here," he said, adding that there was no reason for people to resort to physical abuse against the media. \par \par \uc2  Alliance of Independence Journalists (AJI) chairperson Ati Nurbaiti concurred, saying that such violence could cause the media to censor itself, and this was dangerous for the media, given its position as watchdog on the government, the legislature and the judiciary. \par \par \uc2  "Our judicial system and its officials can do nothing (to support the media). Worse, there is nothing significant to prevent violence against the press," said Ati in a statement. \par \par \uc2  Bambang, whose magazine is currently involved in a legal dispute with Tomy, suggested the press council should act as an arbiter to handle disputes involving the media. \par \par \uc2  "People may sue the media in court, but if they choose to settle their dispute with the media through the press council, they need no longer proceed with a lawsuit," he said. \par \par \uc2  Bambang said that the choice would benefit all parties, as not all disputes involving the media needed to be resolved in court, a process that required both time and money. \par \par \uc2  He also suggested the media and press council promote \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the press among the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the authorities in a bid to raise their awareness of press freedom. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030507dz53000gt\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
