\par\par \b \uc2  In for difficult year. \b0\par\par\uc2 864 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Minister of Finance Boediono was not exaggerating in charting out a much more difficult time for both the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management in 2004 due to the combination of unfavorable external and internal factors. \par \par \uc2  The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  with big downside risks despite the successful end of the war in Iraq, and intra-regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities in Asia have been hindered by the threats of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS). \par \par \uc2  Indonesia itself is in for heightened political emotions and turbulence next year when an estimated 130 million voters across the world's largest archipelago state will hold three rounds of general elections, one for national and regional \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  bodies and the other two for president and vice president. \par \par \uc2  Even though money politics will likely fuel bigger \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , general consumer confidence will decline. Likewise business confidence will weaken as investors put most business plans on hold, waiting for the new government and its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stance. \par \par \uc2  No wonder, most analysts predict \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year at a range of 3.3 percent to 3.5 percent, with similar levels expected for the following year. \par \par \uc2  Further clouding the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook is the bigger threat to sound \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management and, consequently, to macroeconomic stability. \par \par \uc2  Boediono told the \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Committee of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Wednesday that if the government did not renew the extended fund facility of the International Monetary Fund after its expiry later this year, the country would be deprived of the chance of getting new debt rescheduling deals from the Paris Club of sovereign creditors. \par \par \uc2  Without the debt-rescheduling facility, the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on foreign debt amortization alone will triple to almost Rp 47 trillion (US$5.2 billion) next year. Further threatening \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability is the bigger sums of government domestic debts (bonds) maturing in 2004 and in subsequent years. Next year, domestic debt principal payments alone will double to Rp 30.5 trillion from Rp 13.5 trillion this year. \par \par \uc2  Hence, total foreign and domestic service burdens (interest and principal payments) next year will take up as much as 41 percent of total domestic revenues. \par \par \uc2  How will the government cover this? \par \par \uc2  Increasing the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  from this year's level of 1.78 percent of gross domestic product is politically unfeasible as the National Five-Year Development Program (2000-2004) mandates a zero \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year. \par \par \uc2  Such a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  stance also would make the market jittery, increase sovereign risk thereby raising the costs of government borrowing (T-bond coupon), heighten inflationary pressures and increase downward pressure on the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  Increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues is extremely difficult amid low \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Even the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipt target this year is already a tall order due to the recent sharp cuts in the luxury sales \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on many goods. Oil and natural gas \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues are not so promising either in view of the downward trend in international oil prices. Boediono himself assumes a price range of $17 per barrel to $20 per barrel next year, down from $22 per barrel to $23.50 per barrel this year. \par \par \uc2  The privatization of state companies, which is tasked with raising Rp 8 trillion this year, is even more difficult. Not even one of the two dozen state firms selected for divestment has thus far been sold, due to political opposition from many House members. \par \par \uc2  The political climate for privatization next year is expected to be much more hostile as many politicians will likely tend to whip up narrow-minded nationalist sentiment against foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, most foreign investors are now jittery about taking stakes in state companies after the wave of political and legal entanglements faced by privatized companies such as PT Indosat late last year. \par \par \uc2  Asset recovery by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) will no longer produce big proceeds as most of the prize assets under the agency's management have been disposed of. Its sales revenue target of Rp 26 trillion this year could be the peak of IBRA's asset recovery before the end of its mandate next February. \par \par \uc2  Bigger loans from the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) creditor consortium are also virtually impossible, especially if the government decides not to extend its IMF-supervised reform program. The most the government can expect from the CGI next year is as large as its total pledges of $2.7 billion this year. \par \par \uc2  Boediono said he was still optimistic about checking the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at one percent of GDP next year, provided all branches of the government are united with strong determination to push ahead with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms and to maintain high \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline. \par \par \uc2  But this is quite a big appeal as most governments tend to pursue populist measures in an election year. Moreover, virtually the whole government, from the President and vice president down to Cabinet ministers, House members, governors and district chiefs will be preoccupied with campaigning for their respective political parties. \par \par \uc2  The ominous signals conveyed by Boediono should serve as a strong warning to the government, including the House, to stick to the reform agenda and to seriously consider extending the IMF-supervised reform program at least for one year. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030507dz550005q\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
