\par\par \b \uc2  Govt 2004 oil price target too conservative - Subroto. \b0\par\par\uc2 447 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  A'an Suryana, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Former energy minister Subroto said on Monday that the government's oil price assumption of US$17 to $20 per barrel in the proposed 2004 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft was too conservative. \par \par \uc2  Subroto, a former secretary-general of OPEC, said it was unlikely that oil prices would immediately plunge to that level once Iraq quit the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. \par \par \uc2  Subroto told The Jakarta Post that Iraq would require a huge investment and another four years to boost oil production beyond the prewar level of 2.5 million barrels per day. \par \par \uc2  He explained that a very low oil price assumption would limit government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development programs, which is crucial to push \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and create more jobs. \par \par \uc2  He suggested an oil price assumption of $20 to $22 per barrel. \par \par \uc2  The country's state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been heavily depended on revenue from oil for decades. \par \par \uc2  The current 2003 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumes an oil price of $22 per barrel. \par \par \uc2  The government is currently in the process of debating the proposed 2004 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft with \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Commission IX on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and finance. \par \par \uc2  Separately, Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Purnomo Yusgiantoro said on Monday that the decision to propose a lower oil price assumption in next year's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  was based on rising \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the world oil market as Iraq was likely to quit OPEC. \par \par \uc2  "The key is Iraq. If Iraq quits OPEC, then the price of oil may continue to fall, and it will certainly affect our state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumption," Purnomo told reporters. \par \par \uc2  There has been growing speculation that Iraq will leave the oil cartel ever since the fall of Baghdad. There are fears that if it does, Iraq, which has the world's second largest oil \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  of around 250 billion barrels after Saudi Arabia, would boost production and flood the market with oil. \par \par \uc2  This concern has helped push oil prices down to around $25 per barrel compared to around $40 in the run-up to the Iraq war. \par \par \uc2  The U.S. is keen to see Iraq leave OPEC to push oil prices down and help the former's weak \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grow. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, Iraq is tempted to quit OPEC in a bid to pump out more oil to help finance the reconstruction of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  after the war. \par \par \uc2  But Subroto predicted that Iraq would not be able to boost its oil production to six million barrels per day before 2007, and next year the country's output would likely only reach 3.5 million barrels per day. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030506dz560000o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
