s 51 percent stake in Bank Danamon to a consortium led by Singapore's Temasek Holdings had lifted sentiment in the local currency. \par \par \uc2  The Bank Danamon sale does not only mean more dollars to come in, but is also a strong indication that the government is highly committed to carrying out its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program. \par \par \uc2  The surge in the rupiah boosted sentiment in the Jakarta Stock Exchange, pushing the index one percent higher at 463.61, the highest level this year. Traders also said that the sale of Bank Danamon had encouraged investors to buy other blue chip companies. \par \par \uc2  The government is also planning to sell another 20 percent stake in Bank Danamon through the stock market. \par \par \uc2  Thanks to a controllable inflation, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been cutting its benchmark interest rate in recent past months. \par \par \uc2  More good news came from the country's trading performance. The Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) reported last week a nearly 16 percent rise in exports in the first quarter compared to the same period last year pushed by higher prices of commodities. The higher export revenue helped increase the country's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to a record US$33 billion. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030507dz5700002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
