\par\par \b \uc2  Businesses back IMF's monitoring role. \b0\par\par\uc2 660 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Fitri Wulandari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The business sector has demanded that the government continue working with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) through a post-program monitoring system, saying the fund's presence is still crucial to maintain international confidence in the country. \par \par \uc2  "We agree that the IMF program should not be extended (when it ends later this year), but we can't get rid of it (IMF) all at once because it lends credibility," Sofjan Wanandi, chairman of the National Committee for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery (KPEN), said in a media briefing on Friday. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, he said, the only alternative after the contract with the IMF expires at the end of this year is to proceed with post-program monitoring. \par \par \uc2  The IMF's presence, Sofjan said, not only brings financial support, but more importantly lends confidence. \par \par \uc2  "Capital inflows are still good now because investors are confident that the government can carry out \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms under the IMF," he said. \par \par \uc2  Sofjan added that if the government chose to cut ties with the IMF altogether and repay its debt to the fund, amounting to around US$8 billion, investor confidence in Indonesia would likely drop as the country's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  would also decrease from the current level of $33 billion. \par \par \uc2  "It would raise Indonesia's country risk and this would make it more difficult for us to compete internationally. It would be more costly to do business," he said. \par \par \uc2  Post-program monitoring is a requirement for IMF members who complete its program. Under the arrangement, IMF would only monitor how the government carries out structural \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms. \par \par \uc2  Severing ties with the IMF also means that Indonesia would likely lose access to the debt rescheduling facility from the Paris Club. \par \par \uc2  However, staunch critics of IMF say the government should completely cut ties with the fund to allow more room for maneuver for faster \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  They contend that the IMF had failed to save Indonesia from the crisis in 1998 and its rigid, textbook \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies had prolonged the crisis. \par \par \uc2  They also argue that the IMF forced Indonesia to liberalize its market at a faster pace, which had victimized domestic producers. \par \par \uc2  Economist Sri Mulyani Indrawati, IMF executive director for the Southeast Asia region, said totally settling the IMF loan would send the wrong signal to the market, create panic and eventually threaten the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "When the market sees Indonesia's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  drop, they would think there must be something wrong with our country," Sri said at a discussion on Friday. \par \par \uc2  It would unsettle the market. And when the market panics, it influences all \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators such as exchange rates, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and inflation. Eventually, it would influence our balance of payment and deplete the already low foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  She said other Asian countries that were in a healthy \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition were racing to increase their foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to regain market confidence. \par \par \uc2  "Don't force payment of the whole IMF loan just to get rid of it. Market confidence is important," Sri stressed. \par \par \uc2  Sofjan underlined that the IMF's presence was still crucial to monitor the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline, particularly in the current \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  political situation with the possibility of military action in Aceh and the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections. \par \par \uc2  "Political pressure could force the government to spend more money," he said. \par \par \uc2  As the end of IMF program nears, debate on how Indonesia should continue \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform is increasing. \par \par \uc2  Previously, the IMF gave three options for completion of the current arrangement. They are a "standby arrangement", a "precautionary standby arrangement" or completely ending the arrangement, which means Indonesia automatically will be put under post-program monitoring. \par \par \uc2  Both standby arrangement and precautionary standby arrangement would still give Indonesia access to special loans from the IMF upon approval of its reform programs. \par \par \uc2  However, Indonesia would not have access to debt rescheduling facilities with the precautionary standby arrangement and post-program monitoring. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030512dz5a0005n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
