\par\par \b \uc2  Japan to continue support for RI. \b0\par\par\uc2 590 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Fitri Wulandari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The Japanese government remains committed to provide financial support for Indonesia after the latter ends the existing International Monetary Fund program later this year, an envoy said. \par \par \uc2  "The Japanese government will continue to support the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program of the government of Indonesia. We are ready to provide necessary assistance," Japan's Deputy Ambassador to Indonesia Shigekazu Sato told reporters in a media briefing on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  "But, the IMF's role in securing confidence and credibility is undeniable. Therefore, the Indonesian government has to maintain that confidence and credibility," he added. \par \par \uc2  Top government officials have said that the government would not renew the current IMF program when it ends later this year. \par \par \uc2  This has raised concern about the condition of the country's state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as without the presence of the IMF, Indonesia would no longer be able to obtain a debt rescheduling facility from the Paris Club of lender nations. But proponents said that Indonesia would be able to survive the post-IMF era with the current huge foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  of more than US$34 billion, and the healthy macroeconomy. \par \par \uc2  There are also doubts whether the government could implement a credible \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program on its own. The IMF backing of the previous reform program has been essential in securing investor confidence and in lending credibility to the program. \par \par \uc2  Sato said his government would provide new loans, grants and technical assistance, through the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) as well as through bilateral arrangements. \par \par \uc2  The Japanese government is also ready to provide \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  advisors should Indonesia need to design its own post-IMF \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program, Sato added. \par \par \uc2  Japan is currently Indonesia's top donor country, contributing some $2.23 billion in financial assistance for 2003. This represents a third of Indonesia's total external financing needs of around $6.3 billion. \par \par \uc2  Asked whether Japan will increase its financial assistance in 2004 if Indonesia goes ahead and ends the IMF program, Sato only said it would be discussed in the future. \par \par \uc2  However, he expressed confidence that the Indonesian government would manage to maintain \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline so that next year's \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would not be higher than this year's estimate of 1.8 percent of gross domestic product. \par \par \uc2  "The Indonesian government is committed to lowering the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and we are watching them. The government should endeavor to cut down expenses and increase revenue so that, it won't need higher international financing," he said. \par \par \uc2  The government is projecting a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 1 percent of GDP for 2004. \par \par \uc2  On private investment, the embassy's first secretary on financial affairs Hiroshi Ogushi said Japanese investors were still very interested in investing in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  "Big Japanese companies are still interested in putting their money here. They meet regularly with Indonesia's key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers every three months," he said. \par \par \uc2  But Hiroshi acknowledged Japanese investors were facing several problems particularly legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , labor disputes and poor infrastructure. \par \par \uc2  Although Japanese foreign direct investment (FDI) in Indonesia has been shrinking in value, Japan is still the top investor here. \par \par \uc2  For the period of 1967 to 2001, Japanese investors cumulatively made up 14.4 percent of the total FDI, ahead of England (12.1 percent) and the U.S. (4.4 percent). \par \par \uc2  Hiroshi suggested that apart from seeking international financing, the government should maximize domestic revenue such as through the bonds market. \par \par \uc2  "The bonds market is very healthy and it is a good financing source," he said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030514dz5e0000r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
