\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  fallout of Aceh war will spread. \b0\par\par\uc2 729 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Martin P.H. Panggabean, Visiting Researcher, Institute of Southeast Asian, StudiesThe Straits Times, Asia News Network, Singapore \par \par \uc2  It shouldn't just be the people of Aceh who are concerned that last-minute peace negotiations have failed in Tokyo, and that war is now imminent. People in neighboring Sumatran provinces, as well as those in countries such as Singapore, Malaysia and Thailand should be concerned too. \par \par \uc2  What the people of this region need least at this time is another source of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The region has been battered by bad news since September 2001. \par \par \uc2  There are those who think Aceh is too small and insignificant for war there to matter much. After all, they argue, the province's contribution to Indonesia's gross domestic product has continued to dwindle, from 3.6 percent in 1990 to only 2.2 percent in 2001 (the year for which the latest provincial data is available). \par \par \uc2  The only time Aceh appeared in the news in the context of an important \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  story was in relation to its gas field in Arun/Lhok Semauwe. These oil/gas fields are operated jointly by Indonesian government-owned Pertamina, Exxon-Mobil and Jilco, a Japanese company. \par \par \uc2  Even in the oil and gas business, Aceh's contribution to Indonesia's GDP has continued to decline, from 13 percent in 1990 to only 5 percent in 2001, partly due to the substantial depletion of its gas \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  after years of exploration. \par \par \uc2  Aceh's contributions in other \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors have also been minimal. Agriculture contributed to only 3.6 percent of the nation's 2001 agricultural output, while manufacturing's share contracted from 4.2 percent in 1990 to only 1.8 percent in 2001. Other sectors exhibit the same tendency. \par \par \uc2  Given these statistics, it is easy to ignore Aceh. \par \par \uc2  But war in Aceh will have regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  implications, through Aceh's interaction with other provinces, both directly and indirectly. Those provinces may, in turn, have commercial linkages with Indonesia's neighboring countries. \par \par \uc2  A protracted war in Aceh will disrupt production activities there. Given Aceh's status as a supplier of primary products to other regions, a production disruption will, first and foremost, hurt the Aceh \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  itself. Some studies show the estimated impact to be a 14 percent decline in output. \par \par \uc2  By making it difficult for Aceh businesses to maintain their production schedules, the war will also hamper the province's ability to supply raw materials to other regions. My estimates show that the entire island of Sumatra, outside Aceh, can be expected to suffer an output contraction of almost 11 percent, with the brunt borne by South Sumatra (6.7 percent), followed by North Sumatra (1.3 percent) and Riau (1.1 percent). \par \par \uc2  The combined provinces in Java will have their output reduced by 0.6 percent as a result of Aceh's inability to supply raw materials, while the rest of Indonesia will feel only minor \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  effects. \par \par \uc2  The biggest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact of the impending Aceh war will be through the disruption of oil and gas delivered from Aceh. This implies that if the war cannot be avoided, the next best thing that the Indonesian government can do to minimize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact would be to secure the oil and gas fields around Aceh and the shipping routes. \par \par \uc2  But even if the oil and gas fields are secured, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact of the war on other regions cannot be completely eliminated. \par \par \uc2  For the Indonesian government, there are clear \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives to settle the Aceh situation peacefully. A peaceful solution will put less pressure on the already-strained state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and will indirectly help the country's image in the eyes of foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  But war or no war, it is imperative for the Indonesian government to implement a new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development paradigm in Aceh. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  mishandling has turned a once-rich province into one of the poorest and slowest-growing. Its people are suspicious of foreign influence. Such a vicious circle of poverty and suspicion must be eliminated if the welfare of the people is to be increased. This, of course, is also in the best interests of neighboring countries along the Malacca Straits. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  well-being of the Acehnese is best represented by those who speak and act in peace. Unfortunately, this message gets lost at the negotiating table. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030523dz5m00068\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
