\par\par \b \uc2  Travel industry seeks financial aid to weather multiple crisis. \b0\par\par\uc2 648 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Fitri Wulandari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The country's travel industry has asked the government for a subsidized credit facility to help travel agencies battle the collapsing tourism business due to the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) and other \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Chairwoman of the Association of Indonesian Travel Agents (ASITA) Meity Robot said travel agents needed "emergency soft loans" to make up serious cash-flow deficits for at least six months, to avoid bankruptcy. \par \par \uc2  "We have never asked the government to provide credit for us even during the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis that began in 1997. But this time (the problem) is too much. The travel industry is on the brink of bankruptcy," Meity told The Jakarta Post on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  Meity said that due a huge decrease in tourists, both coming and going, travel agents have been forced to close down their outlets, cut salaries, cut operational costs, cut working hours, give long unpaid leave and lay off their workers. \par \par \uc2  "If this continues, travel agents will not be able to pay their obligations. A further drop in tourism business would follow suit," Meity said in the proposal. \par \par \uc2  ASITA, at present, has some 2,500 members nationwide. \par \par \uc2  While saying that ASITA had yet to come up with a sum for the requested credit facility, Meity applauded the \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  package provided by the Malaysian government to SARS-affected businesses. \par \par \uc2  The Malaysian government announced on Wednesday a US$1.92 billion \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  package for SARS-affected industries. It includes a one billion ringgit relief fund, interest rate cuts and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  breaks for the tourist-related companies. \par \par \uc2  The requested subsidized credit facility is part of a \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  package proposed by ASITA to five ministers as reported by this paper earlier. \par \par \uc2  Other measures include reinstating the free visa-on-arrival facility, abolishing value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on tour operators and abolishing the Rp 1 million fiskal, or departure \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , for anybody traveling abroad. \par \par \uc2  ASITA sent the proposal to the offices of the Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare, the State Minister for Culture and Tourism, the State Minister for State Enterprises and the Ministry of Manpower and Transmigration. \par \par \uc2  Although Indonesia is not a SARS-infected country, the tourism industry has still had to face the brunt of the outbreak as many regular tourists and businesspeople normally go to and come from countries that have been hit. The impact has been even more severe than the Bali Bombing last year as it has also discouraged people from traveling outside Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Reservation system company PT Abacus Indonesia revealed that airline bookings for international flights from Indonesia had dropped by 60 percent during March and April, compared to the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  The number of foreign arrivals in March was 288,417, or 30 percent lower than same period in 2002. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, President Megawati Soekarnoputri, in a meeting with The Indonesian Hotel and Restaurants Association (PHRI) and ASITA, on Thursday could only suggest that the cash-strapped tourist-related businesses spend more money on an "international campaign to promote Indonesia as a safe travel destination." \par \par \uc2  PHRI chairwoman Yanti Sukamdani Hardjoprakoso, quoting the President, said travel advisories imposed by several countries to Indonesia were no longer necessary because security had been improving and Indonesia was not a SARS-infected country. \par \par \uc2  Megawati told the industry players to aggressively promote Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  According to Yanti, several western European countries such as Germany, the Netherlands and Italy have lifted their travel advisories. The U.K. still has travel advisories in place, but does not advise its citizen against traveling to Indonesia. And Japan has lowered its travel advisories. \par \par \uc2  Yanti added the hotel occupancy rates had hit rock-bottom. Occupancy rates in Batam have now plunged to around 25 percent, Bali 20 percent to 25 percent and Jakarta 35 percent. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030523dz5n0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 France Provides Debt Swap in Two Sectors.   \b0\par\par\uc2 519 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 May 2003\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 The French government will try to provide Indonesia with the debt swap in the plantation and environment transfer through intensive approach done by the French's Department of Agriculture to the French's Department of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Financial and Industry.   \par \par \uc2 "On the bilateral visit between Indonesian and France, French's Minister of Agriculture Herve Gaymard lobbied French's Minister of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Financial and Industry Francis Mer to swap some of Indonesia's debts, but there has been no talk on that up to this date," said Adian Silalahi, Indonesian ambassador for France to Bisnis' journalist Rofikoh Rokhim in France yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 The clauses proposed for the debt swap, he informed, was by converting some of Indonesia's debts to the preserving of plantation and forest through the rules of sugar palm and other forestry plants intercropping in the plantation and forest areas.   \par \par \uc2 Sililahi said there were many benefits gained from the clauses, which were forest preservation, the plantation plant diversification, and the new sugar source alternative to sugar cane. "Moreover, it can lead to the sustainable development and reduce poverty."   \par \par \uc2 Structural Problems   \par \par \uc2 In the meantime, in Jakarta Deputy Governor of BI Bunbunan Hutapea said the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was unresponsive to the diverse macro and monetary indicator improvements since it was still haunted by structural problems.   \par \par \uc2 He said that high risk in the real sector posed by the structural problems, such as the legal and investment \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by the regional autonomy, the labor issues, and the security condition, made it difficult to manage the sources of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 "Especially the sources come from the investment or export," he said to Bisnis after a discussion entitled Indonesian Prospect for 2004 last week.   \par \par \uc2 Hutapea explained the relatively controlled foreign currency exchange, the below-target circulating primary money, and the inflation rate decrease showed there were monetary condition improvements.   \par \par \uc2 He disclosed that the moderate interaction between demand and supply, the improved inflation expectation, and the muscular rupiah exchange were factors that contributed to the low inflation rate. Overall, the annual inflation rate (year on year) in April 2003 was 7.54%.   \par \par \uc2 In the discussion, economist at Danareksa Research Institute Raden Pardede observed the prospect of the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2004 still existed although it was bright enough to create job opportunities. "It starts to walk, but yet to run."   \par \par \uc2 Pardede stated the structural improvement in the investment prospect still went slow, while the export prospect showed no improvement at all including the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , competitiveness, global demand, and competition with other countries.   \par \par \uc2 Separately, economist Lin Che Wei argued that the post-IMF LoI \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospect would depend on the commitment to enforce the good corporate governance (GCG) by, among other things, continuing the privatization process.   \par \par \uc2 He said that post-crisis Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  faced some image-tarnishing cases concerning the GCG, such as the Manulife, Bank Bali, Semen Cibinong, Bank Lippo, and Asia Pulp and Paper scandals.   \par \par \uc2 "Post-crisis Indonesia faces some big cases that affect our image concerning the GCG. However, only few of the cases that attract the attention of the multinational agencies." (06/07).    \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020030526dz5q0002y\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
