\par\par \b \uc2  Centennial forecasts slower  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  growth this year. \b0\par\par\uc2 488 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Fitri Wulandari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Increasing stability in the country's macroeconomic picture may not translate into speedier \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth due to lingering \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in other parts of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Singapore-based Centennial Asia Advisory is predicting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow at a slower rate of 3 percent this year, from 3.7 percent last year, and only slightly pick up next year to 3.3 percent. \par \par \uc2  "While global demand will, I think, rebound in the third quarter of this year, the overall outlook doesn't seem to be sufficiently positive to see a sharp rebound in growth," Centennial CEO Manu Bhaskaran said in an e-mail response to The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  The government estimates this year the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow by 4 percent, and 4 percent to 5 percent in 2004. \par \par \uc2  Achieving higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is crucial for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be able to absorb the millions of unemployed people. \par \par \uc2  But Bhaskaran said that a slowing down in consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the 2004 general election approached would slow down \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has been the main driver of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth during the past few years, has started to slow down in the first quarter of this year amid a growing unemployment problem. The Central Statistics Agency (BPS) said last week that household consumption during the quarter fell 1.23 percent from the previous quarter, the main reason for the slower growth rate during the quarter. \par \par \uc2  On the external front, Bhaskaran said that Indonesia would face tougher competition from other countries in the region like China and Vietnam, both in the export market and in attracting foreign investment. \par \par \uc2  He added that the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome in the region and fears of terrorism were negatively affecting the tourism sector. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, economist Anton Gunawan of Citibank in Jakarta said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could still grow by 4 percent this year as significant improvement in the macroeconomic environment, as reflected in the stronger rupiah, benign inflation and lower interest rate environment, would push investment and domestic consumption upward. \par \par \uc2  He added that the 2004 general election would also cause the government to spend more money, which was good for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  He said that growth in the telecommunications, transportation and agriculture sectors would be significant contributors to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  "Four percent is, of course, still not good enough, but let's give credit to the improving situation - it's not all negative," Anton told the Post on the phone. \par \par \uc2  He added that despite competition from other economies in the region in the export market, Indonesia was still leading in the area of natural resource-based exports, such as oil, gas and mining. \par \par \uc2  Indeed, exports in the first quarter of this year rose by more than 15 percent compared with the same period last year, due to higher oil and gas exports. \