\par\par \b \uc2  More travel agents may close as business gets worse. \b0\par\par\uc2 975 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  17 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Sudibyo M. Wiradji, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The outbreak of deadly Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) has dealt a major blow to the country's tourism industry. This article and the other two stories in this special page highlight the impact of the flu-like ailment on the industry. \par \par \uc2  Worldwide travel fears resulting from the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) has brought the country's travel industry almost to a standstill. \par \par \uc2  Canceled visits by foreign visitors and flight cuts by major foreign airlines have severely affected tourist activities, putting the already travel industry in its worst ever predicament. \par \par \uc2  "A number of travel agents have been forced to close their offices or lay off employees. Some have offered employees unpaid leave or reduced work hours to enable them to get through this tough time," the chairperson of the Association of Indonesian Tour and Travel Agencies (ASITA), Meity Robot, said. \par \par \uc2  She warned that if the market did not show any improvement within the next two months, most travel agencies would be forced to close their doors. \par \par \uc2  The number of foreign tourist arrivals peaked at 5.18 million in 1997 but dropped to 4.60 million in 1998 and 4.72 million in 1999, due to the combination of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in security following the change in the country's leadership. \par \par \uc2  Tourism began to pick up in 2000, with foreign tourist arrivals rising to 5.06 million, but the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks halted the positive trend, with a relatively slight increase of 5.15 million foreign visitors recorded during the year. Foreign tourist arrivals plunged to 4.3 million in 2002 due to the shocking images of the Bali bombing and foreign media reports about Indonesia as a haven for international terrorist groups. \par \par \uc2  The industry saw signs of recovery in January and February of this year after the adverse effects of the Bali bombing started to wear off in people's minds. \par \par \uc2  But the recent Iraq war and the outbreak of the deadly flu-like SARS immediately reversed that encouraging trend. The latest travel woes have brought the tourist industry to its lowest level in years. \par \par \uc2  Executives of companies involved in tourism-related businesses have strongly criticized the government for not doing enough to support the ailing industry. \par \par \uc2  Instead of lending its support to the devastated travel industry, the government issued early last month a presidential decree to revoke the visa-free facility given to nationals of 48 countries since 1983. A government official said that a visitor could be charged between US$40 and $45 for a visa-on-arrival. \par \par \uc2  Critics have called the move to revoke the visa-free facility "ridiculous", especially at a time when tourism was in serious trouble. \par \par \uc2  "Charging (tourists) for the visa will further worsen the already battered tourist industry," said travel portal Indo.com CEO Eka Ginting. \par \par \uc2  Travel company Panorama president director Satriyanto Tirtawisata shared Eka's view, saying that the government's decision to revoke the visa-free facility had dealt another heavy blow to the nation's shattered tourist industry. \par \par \uc2  "The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not only unnecessary but also counterproductive. It complicates things right in the midst of the survival game for most tourist industry players," he said. \par \par \uc2  Like Satriyanto, Ika Nazaruddin, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations manager of Pacto travel company, also supported the appeal to cancel the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to remove the visa-free facility. \par \par \uc2  ASITA which groups about 3,000 tour and travel agents, has suggested the government to issue a \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  package to keep travel companies afloat instead of removing the visa-free facility. \par \par \uc2  ASITA's chairperson Meity said the \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  package could include low-interest rate loans, which were needed to prevent companies reliant on the tourist trade from closing. \par \par \uc2  Besides proposing an extension of subsidized loans, ASITA also appealed to the government to abolish a value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed on tour operators. \par \par \uc2  "Abolishing the value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and departure \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  could act as an incentive for encouraging people to start traveling, and would in turn salvage the ailing tourist industry," Panorama's Satrijanto said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile Pacto's Ika Nazaruddin said that compared to the Iraq war, SARS had had an even worse effect on our business because the majority of tourists come from Europe. \par \par \uc2  Pacto has seen a 70 percent drop in sales due to the Bali bombing, the Iraq war and fears of SARS. Before the Bali tragedy, Pacto used to annually handle travel arrangements for 50,000 foreign visitors, who traveled throughout the archipelago. "They were mostly from European countries, such as the Netherlands, Germany and France," she said. \par \par \uc2  Similarly, Indo.com, the country's largest travel portal, saw a 75 percent drop in international bookings. "We had begun to recover in January and were back up to almost half the normal numbers. But because of the war and SARS, the recovery process ground to a halt in March," said Eka Ginting of Indo.com. \par \par \uc2  Vaya Tour also saw a significant drop in its sales of inbound services, especially after the outbreak of SARS. It suffered a 70 percent drop in outbound tour sales. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Hotel and Restaurant Association (PHRI) said that since the outbreak of SARS, the country's hotel occupancy rate has dropped significantly, with Batam, Medan and Bali hardest hit. \par \par \uc2  Currently, the country's average hotel occupancy rate is around 30 percent. \par \par \uc2  The SARS has caused hotel occupancy rate in Batam, a favorite destination for Singaporeans, to drop significantly to 20 percent because many travelers from Singapore have canceled their visits. \par \par \uc2  The association also said that the average hotel occupancy rate in Bali was around 25 percent. "With 25 percent occupancy rate, a hotel is facing serious financial problem," said PHRI's Executive Director Carla Parengkuan. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030527dz5s0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
