\par\par \b \uc2  MNCs plans to shift investment from China to Batam. \b0\par\par\uc2 402 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 May 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Adianto P. Simamora \par \par \uc2  , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  A number of multinational companies (MNCs) are planning to shift their investments from China to other countries in the region which were not greatly affected by SARS, according to an expert. \par \par \uc2  Representative of the Hong Kong-based Political and \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Risk Consultancy (PERC) Eddy Mardaus was quoted by \par \par \uc2  Antara \par \par \uc2   as saying on Thursday that some of the investors were eying Batam Island as a possible investment target. \par \par \uc2  But Eddy said that many of the investors were still in doubt because of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  created by a delay in the plan to turn Batam into a Free Trade Zone. \par \par \uc2  Eddy said that the outbreak of the Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) in China and Singapore had forced many MNCs to reformulate strategies in expanding their businesses. \par \par \uc2  Some of the MNCs expressed interest in investing in Batam during an investment forum in the island on May 27 and May 28, in which Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti also attended. \par \par \uc2  Eddy said that many well-known foreign investors showed interest in investing in Batam, including General Electric, Motorola, Ciba, P&O Nedllyod, International Financial Corporation (IFC), Pegasus Capital and JP Morgan. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, PERC managing director Robert C. Broadfoot said that Batam would likely to be the first option for expansion if the government could maintain a conducive investment climate on the island. \par \par \uc2  One of the crucial tasks that needs to be settled quickly is on the Free Trade Zone (FTZ) status plan for Batam. \par \par \uc2  Batam has for many years been a de facto FTZ, and the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives originally intended for export-oriented industries have also been enjoyed by Batam residents and local firms on the island with products and services that are not destined for export. \par \par \uc2  This prompted the finance ministry in 1998 to reimpose the value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (VAT) on Batam to raise revenue for the cash-strapped central government. However, after strong protests from foreign investors the VAT \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was postponed. \par \par \uc2  The finance ministry then extended the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  facilities while awaiting the enactment of a law to give the island the FTZ status. \par \par \uc2  FTZ status for Batam would mean that companies operating on the island, which is located just 20 kilometers from Singapore, would be allowed to import goods without paying customs duties and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  pending their eventual processing, transshipment or reexport. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030602dz5v000bu\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
