\par\par \b \uc2 RI HAS NEVER PREVENTED FOREIGN PRESS FROM COVERING ACEH - MINISTRY SPOKESMAN.  \b0\par\par\uc2 525 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 June 2003\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.  \par \par \uc2 Jakarta, June 13 (ANTARA) - Indonesia's Foreign Affairs Ministry on Friday denied that the Indonesian government has prevented foreign journalists from covering the military offensive in Aceh.  \par \par \uc2 "We have never prevented foreign journalists from covering the various events in Aceh, so long as they follow the regulations. These are only for security reasons," ministry spokesman, Marty Natalegawa, told a press briefing here.  \par \par \uc2 On the previous day, the Indonesian military officers called on an American journalist, William Nessen, to leave the Free Aceh Movement (GAM) rebels by June 14 because beyond that date, the Indonesian military could no longer guarantee his safety.  \par \par \uc2 The Indonesian military's call came after Jakarta said Thursday it had received a letter from a world organization, asking that Indonesian security forces try to pick Nassen, who was in the GAM stronghold in Nisam district, North Aceh.   \par \par \uc2 \f2 \par  \par     Marty said that the government has expressed regret over the\par still \f28 \b \highlight22\uc2 \f2 uncertain\f28 \b0 \highlight\uc2 \f2  fate of the American journalist and was trying its\par trying its best to save him.\par     Aceh military operations commander, Brig Gen Bambang Darmono,\par said that Nessen should report to the military by 6 p.m. on\par Saturday, at the latest.\par     Within the deadline, his safety could be guaranteed, Bambang\par said, adding that Nessen could call him on his cellular phone at\par 0811-961046 anytime.\par     He said Nessen has been with the rebels for a month, even before\par Indonesia launched the military operation on May 19.\par  \par                   Violated regulations\par     Meanwhile, the Foreign Affairs Ministry's director for\par   \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 information and the media, Wahid Supriyadi, said Indonesia has been facing difficulties in saving the American journalist because his presence in Aceh itself has violated regulations.  \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 "Nessen obtained a permit from the Indonesian embassy in Singapore, as a permanent correspondent of the San Francisco Chronicle to cover \f28 \b \highlight22\uc2 \f2 economic\f28 \b0 \highlight\uc2 \f2  and business news," Wahid said.   \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 \par  \par     "But in fact, Nessen is covering the war and works for the\par Sydney Morning Herald and the Boston Globe," he said.\par     He pointed out that after getting a permit from the Indonesian\par   \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 Foreign Affairs Ministry to stay in Indonesia from September 2002 to October this year, Nessen did not comply with the next \f28 \b \highlight22\uc2 \f2 regulation\f28 \b0 \highlight\uc2 \f2 , namely getting limited residence permit from Foreign Ministry and get a work permit from the Manpower Ministry.   \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 \par  \par     Nessen also needed a permit to travel from the Indonesian Police\par before going to an area of conflict, he said.\par     The Indonesian Foreign Affairs Ministry has never rejected\par foreign journalists who want to cover the war in Aceh, Wahid\par reiterated.\par     Some 20 foreign journalists are covering the armed conflict in\par   \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 Aceh, their letters of recommendation were given by Foreign Ministry to the Indonesian military headquarters' information affairs, he said.  \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 "The press in Indonesia freely covers everything. There is no prohibition for them. However, they have been requested to follow regulations for the sake of their own safety, and so are foreign journalists, because their safety is the responsibility of the Indonesian government," he said.  \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 The government last month launched a full-scale military operation in Aceh in an effort to crush the GAM, which has been fighting for an independent state since 1976.   \f28 \par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020030614dz6d0005s\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
