\par\par \b \uc2  ' \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty \highlight\uc2  over investment law deters investment'. \b0\par\par\uc2 507 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 June 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Adianto P. Simamora, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Despite the improving political stability and strengthening macroeconomic indicators, many foreign investors remain reluctant to make new investments in the country due to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the issuance of a long-awaited new investment law, Chairman of the Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) Theo Toemion said. \par \par \uc2  "There have been positive progress in other areas, but investors are still waiting for the (new) investment law," he told lawmakers on Wednesday during a hearing session with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Commission V on industry and investment. \par \par \uc2  Theo said that the draft of the investment law, which was planned seven years ago, had been submitted to the Ministry of Justice and Human Rights and was now in the hands of the office of the State Secretary. \par \par \uc2  The new law will replace Law No. 1/1967 on foreign investment and Law No. 6/1968 on domestic investment. \par \par \uc2  Under the draft law, the BKPM will be tasked to set up a one-stop service for providing investment licenses in a bid to speed up the licensing process and cut down on the bureaucracy. This role is apparently opposed by some ministers and regional administrations who would lose their licensing authorities. \par \par \uc2  Another controversial article of the bill involves a proposal to provide investment incentives, including \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  holidays, to lure investors, which has been rejected by the Ministry of Finance. \par \par \uc2  The draft law also aims to ensure equal government treatment to both foreign and domestic investors. \par \par \uc2  "This indicates that the government does not have the political will to attract new investments to the country," legislator Irmadi Lubis said. \par \par \uc2  He urged the government to immediately submit the draft to the House for deliberation. \par \par \uc2  Attracting new investments is seen as crucial in pushing the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow at its potential growth rate of 6 percent per year, in order to absorb the millions of people made jobless by the late-1990s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. The government projects a meager 4 percent growth for this year. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have said that the hard gained appreciation of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar, the declining interest rate and the benign inflation environment had not been able to lure a significant amount of new investments due to lingering problems, such as a weak legal system, rampant labor protests and smuggling activities. \par \par \uc2  Theo said, however, that there had actually been positive progress in resolving these problems. \par \par \uc2  For the past several years, investments - particularly foreign direct investments (FDIs) - have been on a declining trend. In 2002 for example, FDI approvals dropped by 35 percent to US$9.7 billion from $15.06 billion the previous year, while domestic investment approvals plunged by 57 percent to Rp 25.26 trillion from Rp 58.62 trillion. \par \par \uc2  The BKPM reported that realized investment in the first five months of this year reached $918.2 million, out of $4.02 billion in approvals. It did not provide a comparative figure for the same period in the previous year. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030619dz6j0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
