\par\par \b \uc2  Investors complain over 'biased' reporting on RI. \b0\par\par\uc2 559 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 June 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  A'an Suryana, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Several investors have complained about the biased coverage on Indonesia by both local and foreign media, saying that the tarnished image of the country caused by the negative reporting had contributed to the downturn in investments here. \par \par \uc2  "Indonesia's tarnished image, as has been portrayed by the media, has damaged the business confidence. No wonder Indonesia has hardly rated as a place to do business in the last few years," John Arnold, chairman of the British Chamber of Commerce's mission in Indonesia, said during the "Indonesia's Image: Media Myth and Reality" seminar on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  Arnold said that the biased reporting started in 1997 following the multidimensional crisis that hit the country. Since then, Indonesia has been perceived as a country struggling to find itself, rife with ethnic and religious tensions and conflicts, and the collapse of law enforcement and widespread breaking of contracts with impunity. \par \par \uc2  "None of us could convincingly argue that there is no basis for these images," he said. \par \par \uc2  Arnold said that the media had helped create and establish the image, not because of misreporting, but more because of selective reporting. \par \par \uc2  He called on the media to be more balanced in reporting events in Indonesia and not to focus only on security, scandalous and political issues. The coverage of these issues could bring losses to the country's investment climate. \par \par \uc2  Citing an example, Arnold pointed to the Tangguh LNG project being developed by BP Indonesia in Papua, about which the media has focussed on the risk of environmental damage and the failure to secure the first major sales contract with southern China. \par \par \uc2  "There is little (coverage) on the potential \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits that will flow into Papua and Indonesia as a whole," he said. \par \par \uc2  Executive director of Goldman Sachs-Singapore Gita Wirjawan shared Arnold's view, saying that the media had created a perception of Indonesia as identical with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and disarray since several years ago. \par \par \uc2  This would surely impact foreign confidence in Indonesia, as investors would still refer to the biased reporting because of the existing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the country. \par \par \uc2  "Since we are entering the pre-election cycle, there is a relatively high degree of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including the broader issue of the capability of Jamaah Islamiyah (JI) terrorism cells in Indonesia. These \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  seem to have slowed down the return of capital flights and put additional business investments on hold," Gita said in the seminar. \par \par \uc2  Arnold urged the government to learn how to build a good relationship with the media in order to create a better image for investment. \par \par \uc2  "When a potentially embarrassing news event breaks, which will negatively impact the government, there is often a tendency to react with hastily staged press conferences. Platitudes, unconvincing statements or denials will be communicated. Then life goes on," said Arnold. \par \par \uc2  Another speaker at the seminar, Damien Kingsbury, a lecturer at Deakin University in Australia, acknowledged that Indonesia was vulnerable to the unbalanced coverage. \par \par \uc2  However, he defended the media, saying that the biased reporting was actually part of the media's efforts to do good for society as a whole. \par \par \uc2  "The media has a duty as a watchdog, in alerting the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  to current problems and calling on the government and other relevant institutions to be accountable," he said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030620dz6k00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
