\par\par \b \uc2  Asia, EU ministers to boost partnership. \b0\par\par\uc2 691 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 July 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Dadan Wijaksana, The Jakarta Post, Nusa Dua, Bali \par \par \uc2  The fifth Asia-Europe finance ministers meeting concluded on Sunday with participants endorsing the Bali Initiative, aimed at strengthening the partnership for growth and development between the two regions. \par \par \uc2  Under the Bali Initiative, countries in the ASEM (the Asia-Europe Meeting) will boost cooperation among the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial authorities of both regions through programs such as internships, staff exchanges, provision of scholarships, training and others. \par \par \uc2  Well-trained \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials are "critical elements" in a sound \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial system, the ministerial statement said. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia had proposed the initiative as a way to prevent a repeat of the financial crisis that hit most Asian countries in the late 1990s. Some blamed it on the absence of a sound early warning system in the countries. \par \par \uc2  The finance ministers agreed to use the ASEM Trust Fund II to support the program's financing, Indonesian Minister of Finance Boediono said. \par \par \uc2  "No figures as yet. But I'm guessing the amount will not be much different from what we received under the ASEM Trust Fund I," Boediono told reporters after the meeting ended. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia received around US$7.5 million from the ASEM Trust Fund l after it was badly hit by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. Thailand and Malaysia received similar amounts. \par \par \uc2  The trust fund was established to provide financial support to countries in need in the two regions, as well as other purposes deemed beneficial to strengthening relationships among countries in Asia and Europe. \par \par \uc2  Ministers gathered at the two-day meeting painted an upbeat picture of global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. \par \par \uc2  "Although growth among developed countries remains subdued and the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to face short-term \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and challenges, ministers expressed confidence that growth would accelerate up in near future," the ministers said in a closing statement. \par \par \uc2  Ministers remained committed to global efforts to accelerate development, to achieve the global poverty-eradication program called Millennium Development Goals, to reduce the proportion of people living on $1 per day from 29 percent in 1990 to 14.5 percent in 2015. \par \par \uc2  Jemal-ud din Kassum, the World Bank vice president for Asia and the Pacific, said during the ministerial meeting that East Asian countries were on track to meet their Millennium Development Goals despite the setback suffered in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  The meeting also reaffirmed strong commitments to the fight against money laundering and combating the financing of terrorism. \par \par \uc2  With regards to money laundering, the ministers welcomed plans by Germany and Malaysia to co-sponsor a symposium in Germany this October on fighting underground banking in Asia and Europe. \par \par \uc2  Another important issue discussed during the meeting was the planned creation of the Asian Bond Market. \par \par \uc2  "The ministers stressed the importance of fostering a bond market denominated in local currencies, as it could enhance mobilization of savings for long-term investments in the region," the statement said. \par \par \uc2  Asia has planned to create $1 billion worth of Asian Bond Fund, to be used to buy out bonds issued by countries in the region. The first batch of the fund was launched two weeks ago by 11 Asia-Pacific nations, including Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  The ministers described the Thai-initiated bond fund as "catalytic" in stimulating the region's capital markets. \par \par \uc2  The Bali meeting was attended by 10 ASEM Asian member states, 14 European countries, the European Commission, the European \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and three international financial institutions: The World Bank, Asian Development Bank (ADB) and the International Monetary Fund (IMF). \par \par \uc2  The Asian countries were: Indonesia, Brunei, China, Japan, Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. The 14 European nations were: Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal, Spain, Sweden and the United Kingdom. \par \par \uc2  ASEM, which was first held in Thailand in 1996, is a biennial informal meeting of heads of state and governments of 10 Asian countries and 16 EU member states, including the president of the European Commission. \par \par \uc2  In order to facilitate cooperation in various fields, finance, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and foreign ministers meet annually. The ASEM foreign ministers meeting will be held in Bali on July 23-24. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030707dz770000k\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 "Government Should Conduct Road-Shows on Bonds".   \b0\par\par\uc2 499 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 July 2003\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 A government official said that the government needed to conduct a road show to check the interest of the global market to Indonesian bonds following the end of the IMF Program.   \par \par \uc2 The Deputy Senior \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister for International Relation Jannes Hutagalung said that the government should do this as the recent market condition had been different with that before the crisis. He added the government also had to consider the cost of issuing the bond.   \par \par \uc2 "We should find out the best underwriter. We also should conduct a road show and consider the cost of issuing the bond," he told the press when explaining the result of a discussion on Indonesian Country Risk and Credit Rating.   \par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Boediono, meanwhile, said that the government would check the interest of foreign investors and learn the market condition especially the market of United States, European countries and Asian countries.   \par \par \uc2 "We firstly want to talk with investors in the US, Europe and Asia," he said in Jakarta yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 He was optimistic that foreign investors would be interested in Indonesian bonds. He added the issuance of government's bond overseas was just a matter of time.   \par \par \uc2 He said that investors preferred to invest in the government's bond than directly investing in the country.   \par \par \uc2 But Hutagalung was worried that the recent global market could not absorb all of the bonds to be issued.   \par \par \uc2 He added that in 1996 the government issued some Yankee bonds and the market absorbed the all bonds. But the condition had been changing today.   \par \par \uc2 At that time the government issued some US$400 million from the initial plan of US$200 million bond. "The government increased the value because the demand was high."   \par \par \uc2 To Be Issued Next Year   \par \par \uc2 Minister Boediono said that the government would hopefully issue the bonds next year to fill the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  gap as the Paris Club creditors would not reschedule Indonesian debt at that time.   \par \par \uc2 He said in 2004 there would be a financing gap of 4.2% to the GDP and another 3.2% in 2005. The government would fill the gap, among others, by issuing some bonds.   \par \par \uc2 Hutagalung added that every year the matured debt of Indonesian government to the creditors of Paris Club was ranging from USR2.5 billion to US$3 billion.   \par \par \uc2 He added that the government was considering of issuing some Eurobonds, Yankee Bond and Samurai Bond to fill that financing gap.   \par \par \uc2 Commenting on this plan, the former State Minister of State Owned Enterprises Tanri Abeng said that would be better if the bond would be issued by the new government.   \par \par \uc2 He said that investor would wait and see what would happen in Indonesia after the election.   \par \par \uc2 Abeng said that the transitional period between the recent government with the next one would be around one year. So for the investor today was the period of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 He said that the market sentiment was mainly influence by the psychological condition of the market. (07/aph).    \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020030709dz7900007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
