\par\par \b \uc2  Some businesses have no appetite for new loans. \b0\par\par\uc2 582 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 July 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Evi Mariani, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The aggressive campaign by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to persuade banks to cut their rates and make bank loans cheaper, may not necessarily prompt businesses to prepare proposals for new loans. \par \par \uc2  Businessmen interviewed by The Jakarta Post on Thursday said they had no reason to borrow money from the banks, even if rates were significantly lower, because of the limited opportunities for business expansion amid the weak purchasing power of the people and other \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  affecting the business climate. \par \par \uc2  "If I borrow money from a bank to start a new business, there's no guarantee my business will generate profit in this kind of (investment) climate," said Adhi Sukmono, secretary general of the Indonesian Electronic Industries Association, who also runs a dealership for Japan's Toshiba electronic products. \par \par \uc2  He said that the weak purchasing power of consumers was affecting sales in the electronic industry. \par \par \uc2  "If the demand growth for (electronic products) this year reaches, say, 10 percent, my company can still meet the (financing) demand without having to borrow money." \par \par \uc2  For the past year, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been driving down its benchmark interest rate, from over 13 percent earlier this year to 9.23 percent, in a bid to encourage other banks to reduce their lending rates, and allow the corporate sector to borrow more money and expand their businesses. This was hoped to accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and create new jobs. \par \par \uc2  But despite the strong pressure from \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , during the past month, lending rates remained stubbornly high at around 18 percent, although a couple of banks have recently started to lower rates to 17-16 percent, and said that the rates could drop to 14 percent by the year-end. \par \par \uc2  Some banks said that the ideal lending rate should be around 13-14 percent. \par \par \uc2  On Thursday, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Burhanuddin Abdullah said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would soon introduce new measures to help banks lower their lending rates. The new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be directed at further lowering the interest rate for time deposit and savings, which would make the cost of funds cheaper and allow banks to lower lending rates. \par \par \uc2  Anton J. Supit, who runs a shoe manufacturing and poultry businesses said the current favorable macroeconomic condition and the prospect of lower lending rates were no reason for his company to quickly seek a bank loan. \par \par \uc2  "I see that consumer confidence is still low, so if I borrow money and produce more shoes, who will buy them?" he said, adding that shoes sales had been declining recently. \par \par \uc2  He acknowledged that the poultry business was experiencing a healthier outlook than that of shoes but did not plan to expand the food business either. \par \par \uc2  "I use everything I have right now to keep the poultry business going," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said that lower lending rates were necessary, but not a sufficient reason for companies to make new investments because of various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  created by a weak legal system, labor conflicts, and poor implementation of the regional autonomy law. \par \par \uc2  "The government should upgrade the investment climate," Anton said. \par \par \uc2  Businessmen also said that the upcoming 2004 general election and the poor handling of affairs in Aceh were factors deterring them from committing to new investments. \par \par \uc2  But small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) seem to be hungry for cheaper bank loans. \par \par \uc2  "The banking industry should help the SMEs. We need fresh money" said entrepreneur Arfan Sofan. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030711dz7b00007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
