\par\par \b \uc2  Economists say Mega's policies fail to push growth. \b0\par\par\uc2 550 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 August 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies taken by the administration of President Megawati Soekarnoputri have failed to push for the higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth needed to create more jobs, economists say. \par \par \uc2  University of Gadjah Mada (UGM) economist Revrisond Baswir said that the government's tight \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  aimed at strengthening the rupiah and lowering inflation and interest rate have not translated into higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth as investments remain scarce. \par \par \uc2  "The government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is moving in the wrong direction, because it is not in favor of providing the basic needs of the people like food and jobs," he said. \par \par \uc2  "Macroeconomic stability is important, but what's more important is to open up plenty of job opportunities, in which the government has failed because of its tight \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Revrisond said, pointing out that the government's tight \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  had limited \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  for stimulating the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  He was responding to Megawati's speech delivered at the start of the Annual Session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), in which she said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  this year would grow at a slower rate of 3.66 percent compared to the initial projection of 4 percent, as industries had yet to recover from the impact of the 1997-1998 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Megawati did not elaborate on this, although she told lawmakers that her government had managed to stabilize the macroeconomic condition, as reflected in the stronger rupiah, benign inflation and lower interest rate environment. \par \par \uc2  Last year, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  also grew by 3.66 percent. Experts have said that to create enough jobs for the millions of unemployed, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must grow by at least 6 percent per year. \par \par \uc2  The Asian Development Bank earlier predicted that this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would likely reach around 3.4 percent, due to a combination of external and internal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, economist Sri Adiningsih said that macroeconomic stability had not translated into higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth because the government had failed to resolve the various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  faced by businesses such as legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , rampant corruption and labor conflicts. \par \par \uc2  "Now the priority should be to improve our investment climate, thus increasing our global competitiveness," Sri said. \par \par \uc2  Megawati, however, acknowledged that corruption, collusion and nepotism (KKN) still flourished despite relentless campaigns against the practices, and therefore posed a danger to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Up to certain degree, the surge in foreign and national debts and the collapse of our banking system (during the crisis) were directly related to KKN practices. \par \par \uc2  "It is ironic that ... KKN practices now occur collectively among certain politicians, in particular those sitting in regional \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  bodies," she said. \par \par \uc2  Revrisond also strongly criticized the government's privatization drive and asset sales program, because it was a serious threat to workers who may lose their jobs. \par \par \uc2  He explained that the sale of various assets, which have contributed to the inflow of dollars and to strengthening the rupiah, was forced by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), whose main interest was only to see that the country repaid its foreign debts. \par \par \uc2  But the IMF representative, David Nellor in Jakarta applauded the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , saying that the government remained on track to achieve its full-year \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  target, important to maintain macroeconomic stability. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030801dz820000v\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
