\par\par \b \uc2  Rising  \highlight22\uc2 interest rates \highlight\uc2  may derail recovery - Investors. \b0\par\par\uc2 686 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 August 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  14 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Amy Baldwin, Associated Press, New York \par \par \uc2  Wall Street had to face another hard reality this past week: \b \highlight22\uc2 Interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are rising, and threatening to undermine an already \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  Rising rates are "front of mind for everyone," said Mark Jordahl, chief investment officer at U.S. Bancorp Asset Management. \par \par \uc2  The turnaround in rates actually isn't that surprising, but investors nonetheless were unnerved by the idea that higher borrowing costs will deter consumers from \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and companies from expanding. \par \par \uc2  Since the middle of June, the yield on the 10-year Treasury note has risen to about 4.3 percent from just over 3.0 percent, due largely to signals that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is rebounding and the Federal Reserve is being less aggressive about keeping rates lower as an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The stock market has responded with declining prices. \par \par \uc2  "The reason the stock market is essentially stalled out is because not only did \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  rise, but they have risen more sharply than they have at any time since May 1987, and in percentage terms they have risen more sharply since any time since 1962," said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp. \par \par \uc2  Market analysts say the higher rates aren't warranted in an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that remains far from robust, even fragile. \par \par \uc2  "We think the spike in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  is overdone. But if these yields go higher, the recovery we have been hoping for might be a little less robust," said Greg Valliere, chief strategist of Schwab's Washington Research Group, in a report out Friday. \par \par \uc2  Among the data that fail to support the need for higher rates, Valliere cited an unemployment rate of 6.2 percent. He also said there's no evidence to say that inflation is back. \par \par \uc2  Another reason for higher rates is that the Federal Reserve has indicated it will be less aggressive, after having slashed rates 13 times since early 2001 to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The Fed meets on Tuesday, but is widely expected to leave rates unchanged. \par \par \uc2  In his report, Valliere acknowledged that there are signs of strength in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that could be behind the rising rates. For example, corporate inventories fell considerably in the second quarter, according to the Commerce Department's report on the gross domestic product. That suggests that demand for goods is increasing. \par \par \uc2  Aside from a big sell-off on Tuesday, when the Dow Jones industrials dropped 149.72 points, the market handled its fears about \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  rather well this past week. \par \par \uc2  The Dow managed to end the week up 0.4 percent. For the week, the Nasdaq composite index forfeited 4.2 percent, while the Standard & Poor's 500 index declined 0.3 percent. \par \par \uc2  The gauges also remain well above their March 11 lows for the year. The Dow is up 22.2 percent from those lows. The Nasdaq is up 29.3 percent, while the S&P is up 22.1 percent. \par \par \uc2  "It is comforting the equity market has digested the rise in rates so well," Jordahl said. \par \par \uc2  Still, investors are somewhat torn about how to read the higher rates. On the upside, rising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  could signal that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is improving. But the question remains if the rising rates are premature, given the still shaky recovery. \par \par \uc2  "The market is having a tough time (deciding) what the equilibrium interest rate is," said Scott Wren, equity strategist for A.G. Edwards & Sons. And, he added, investors are asking, "Will higher rates choke off \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, or is it a good sign the recovery is going to continue?" \par \par \uc2  Some Wall Street observers remain hopeful that rates will come down and that stocks will recoup their recent losses. \par \par \uc2  Jordahl said, "Our feeling is the run-up (in rates) has run its course." \par \par \uc2  The Dow ended the week up 37.12, closing Friday at 9,191.09. \par \par \uc2  The Nasdaq had a weekly loss of 71.59, finishing at 1,644.03 on Friday. The S&P had a weekly decline of 2.56, closing at 977.59. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030810dz8b0001h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
