\par\par \b \uc2  Curing nation's paranoia toward IMF monitoring. \b0\par\par\uc2 855 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 August 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Julia Puspadewi Tijaja, Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS), Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Despite some opposition from the chief of the National Developing Planning Board (Bappenas) Kwik Kian Gie and former chief \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister Rizal Ramli, our government has come up with the decision to end the IMF's Extended Fund Facilities program with the Post Program Monitoring (PPM) arrangement by end of this year. \par \par \uc2  The nation's previously controversial relationship with the IMF has resulted in a certain degree of hostility toward having the IMF monitoring under the PPM arrangement. \par \par \uc2  IMF has conveniently been made the main scapegoat of our slow and staggering recovery from the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in comparison to other Asian countries. Recommendations made by the IMF were seen to have led Indonesia into a deeper crisis - a naive oversimplification. Yet countries receiving loans from international financial institutions are those already facing an unfavorable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, thus it is hard to know whether Indonesia would be better off without the Fund, and worse still to accuse the IMF program of being the cause of the crisis. \par \par \uc2  Strong criticism was made of the Fund's generic formulation of tight \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in times of crisis. While the latter was justified to put a stop on domestic currency depreciation, the former received more criticism as being insensitive toward the poor. However, the need to tighten our \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mainly arises from our worrying level of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Reckless \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion in the form of project funding often has questionable effective surveillance and accountability at times of political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  instability. Misuse of such funding will lead the country into higher \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , without any stimulative result in our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Despite all these, opponents of international body monitoring tried to give their justification for carrying the nation's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform without PPM. \par \par \uc2  Opponents of PPM were optimistic about the soundness of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Though our macroeconomic indicators have indicated noteworthy improvement, our real sector has yet to be stimulated. Without serious structural adjustment and financial reforms, we should anticipate a reverse flow of our mainly short term capital inflow when there is a sudden drop in market confidence. \par \par \uc2  In a country like Indonesia where market sentiment is highly sensitive to both \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and noneconomic factors, convincing the market of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform commitment is an enormously challenging task. Moreover, in the face of the upcoming election in 2004, there is a stronger need to secure market confidence due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the highly volatile period of political transition. \par \par \uc2  The presence of an internationally recognized monitoring body like the IMF would help secure market confidence. It serves as a strong pillar that signals the government's seriousness at pursuing realistic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform, mitigating market suspicion that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be ill-maintained during the battle for political power. Thus, this will increase the immunity of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to noneconomic domestic shocks. \par \par \uc2  Another advantage of having the IMF as our monitoring body is that we are able to pay our debt to the Fund in installments up until 2010. Despite the fact that our present foreign reserve absolute level of US$34 billion (inclusive of the $9.2 billion owed to the IMF) is strong enough to repay our debts in a lump sum, we should not be too reckless. There is evidence that the market reacts asymmetrically more to negative perception, like in the case when there is a sudden drop in our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Without the PPM arrangement, we have to pay $5.9 billion in a lump sum to bring our debts down to the quota level of $2.8 billion. It is extremely difficult to maintain market confidence when there is substantial fall in the level of our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indeed, the interest we bear is a worthy cost to reduce the risk of another herding capital outflow that we cannot afford. \par \par \uc2  Hence, the option of having an international monitoring body should not be confronted with "nationalistic" hostility and unnecessary paranoia. Under the PPM arrangement, the IMF could not restrict our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , since their approval is not needed in the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -making process. It is their evaluation that will be judged by the market. As long as the government is carrying out policies favorable to market sentiments, there is no reason to worry about the IMF's presence under the PPM arrangement. \par \par \uc2  In this highly mobile world, staying under an internationally recognized monitoring body shows that the government is careful, acting in the best interests of our investors. It helps to promote a conducive atmosphere for investment, which is desperately needed to solve our problem of unemployment. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  actors will definitely have more confidence in a "patient" accepting licensed doctors' monitoring and regular medical consultation by being under PPM. \par \par \uc2  It is now time to prove the government's credibility in undertaking \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms with self-drawn Letter of Intents which are accountable to the nation. \par \par \uc2  The writer is also currently studying for an Economics and Politics degree at Queen Mary, University of London, United Kingdom \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030811dz8b0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
