\par\par \b \uc2  'Credit profile of mobile operators improves'. \b0\par\par\uc2 448 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 August 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  14 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Agence France-Presse, Manila \par \par \uc2  Mobile telephone operators in Southeast Asia are significantly improving their credit profiles on the back of growing subscriber bases and revenues, Moody's Investors Service said on Monday. \par \par \uc2  The ratings agency said all its rated mobile phone issuers in the region exhibited enhanced financial conditions, benefiting from a strong uptake in cellular telecommunications in essentially under-penetrated environments. \par \par \uc2  According to a Moody's study, mobile phones have now become the principal mode for voice transmission in Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines. \par \par \uc2  The study covered only the region's four emerging economies and excluded Singapore, whose cellular market is one of the most competitive in Asia, marked by high penetration rate, with eight out of 10 residents in the city state a mobile subscriber. \par \par \uc2  "Most major operators in these countries - by achieving critical subscriber mass - have secured greater certainty in their abilities to fund growth, access capital markets to refinance maturing debt and provide investors with returns," says Charles Macgregor, Moody's vice president and senior credit officer. \par \par \uc2  "Consequently, Moody's believes that the ability of operators to meet their funding needs - covering investments and maturing debt - has become a diminishing concern," Macgregor said. \par \par \uc2  The report said the credit profiles of the region's mobile operators had improved in the six years since the 1997-1998 Asian financial crisis, partly reflecting enhanced \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals and better technology. \par \par \uc2  "Going forward, given the healthier financial and operating profiles, strategic investor support may not be as critical as before," Moody's said. \par \par \uc2  "And now that the threat of corporate collapse has eased dramatically, for most rated operators it is more an issue of sustaining competitive positions." \par \par \uc2  However, the Moody's report also cautioned that the region's operators were still exposed to "varying degrees of risk from macroeconomic trends, political volatility, and to a lesser extent foreign exchange moves and regulatory changes." \par \par \uc2  The region's regulatory environments currently pose a "moderate level of risk," Moody's said. \par \par \uc2  In the coming 12 to 24 months, Moody's said, decisions by regulators - centering on tariffs and interconnections - were likely to be the next source of regulatory impact on credit profiles. \par \par \uc2  Other challenges include the need to cut costs to grow profits as cellular penetration nears saturation, greater sensitivity to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, shareholder pressure for higher returns and regulatory pressure to keep tariffs low. \par \par \uc2  Macgregor noted the region's telecoms regimes continued to evolve and that the importance of earlier concerns - such as liberalization time frames and competitor numbers - had become less significant. \par \par \uc2  "\b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , however, over issues such as \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  structures, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , access and interconnection regimes persist," he said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020030812dz8c00013\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
