\par\par \b \uc2 Govt sets higher growth target of 5% next year.   \b0\par\par\uc2 649 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 August 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \par \uc2 The government has set a higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of 5 percent for next year under the draft 2004 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be unveiled by President Megawati Soekarnoputri on Friday, Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti said.   \par \par \uc2 "President Megawati will deliver the opening speech for the draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and in it, you will see that our next year's target is 5 percent," he told reporters on Tuesday.   \par \par \uc2 Megawati is also expected to present the government's post-International Monetary Fund (IMF) \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program at the same time.   \par \par \uc2 Dorodjatun did not give reasons for the rather optimistic projection, in spite of various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  both at home and abroad.   \par \par \uc2 During the initial round of talks with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  committee, the government said that in addition to strong domestic consumption, higher exports and investments should help push the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow at a higher rate of between 4 to 5 percent. The government said that an expected recovery in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would help increase exports and investments.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  this year is expected to grow at around 4 percent. Some government officials said the increasing stability in the country's macroeconomic indicators, as reflected in the appreciation of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar, benign inflation and a lower \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  benchmark interest rate, should strengthen the confidence of investors in making fresh investments here.   \par \par \uc2 But many have also said that the 5 percent growth target for next year was too optimistic, considering that 2004 would be a "risky period" for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as the IMF's current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  bailout program expires later this year and the country holds its first direct general elections in April.   \par \par \uc2 Slow progress in resolving the various problems faced by foreign businesses in the country and renewed terrorist threats may cause investors to temporarily shelve their investment plans.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been growing at a modest rate of between 3 to 4 percent over the past couple of years, mainly driven by strong domestic consumption amid weak investments and exports.   \par \par \uc2 Experts have said that for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be able to generate enough jobs for the millions of people made jobless by the 1997-1998 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, the growth rate must be at least 6 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Dorodjatun said that a 6 to 7 percent growth target could be achieved in 2006 or 2007, depending on the pace of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.   \par \par \uc2 "To achieve a 7 percent growth target will not be easy because of the country's huge population, not to mention the impact of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  (recession) and security issues at home, which has been lately undermined by a number of terrorist bombings," Dorodjatun was quoted by Antara as saying.   \par \par \uc2 The higher growth rate next year is expected to help the government cut down its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to around 1 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) from this year's estimated \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 1.8 percent GDP. The government hopes to finance around 70 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  through foreign loans.   \par \par \uc2 Assuming that next year's GDP would grow to Rp 2.037 trillion from this year's estimate of Rp 1.940 trillion, the 2004 \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be Rp 21.34 trillion, which means the government would need about Rp 15 trillion (US$1.81 billion) in new foreign loans.   \par \par \uc2 Key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators   \par \par \uc2 2003 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  expected 2004 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 *   \par \par \uc2 (target) realization   \par \par \uc2 Growth 4.0 3.5-4.0 4.0-5.0   \par \par \uc2 Inflation 9.0 5.0-6.0 6.0-8.0   \par \par \uc2 Rupiah rate (Rp/US$1) 9,000 8,300-8,800 8,200-9,200   \par \par \uc2 3-month SBI** (%) 13.0 10.0-11.0 9.0-10.0   \par \par \uc2 * Based on initial round of talks with the House ** \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  promissory notes   \par \par \uc2 Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post.    \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020030812dz8d0005t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
