\par\par \b \uc2 Liquidity credits cleared.  \b0\par\par\uc2 835 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 August 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 The government and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  finally resolved last week their long-standing dispute over the sharing of the costs of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis with the issuance ofRp 144.5 trillion (US$17 billion) worth of 30-year bonds to reimburse the emergency liquidity support the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  extended in 1997 and 1998 to bail out the distressed banking industry.  \par \par \uc2 The bonds, with an annual interest of 0.1 percent would replace the debt instruments worth the same amount the government issued in 1998 and 1999 to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 This deal resolved once and for all the four-year dispute over the massive liquidity credits that arose after the Supreme Audit Agency found in 1999 that Rp 138.5 trillion of the loans had not been adequately secured with collaterals and quite a portion of these funds, supposed to reimburse depositors during the massive bank runs, had been misused by the recipient banks in currency speculation or lending to their affiliated businesses.  \par \par \uc2 The audit's findings prompted the government to disclaim any responsibility to reimburse the credits and threatened to withdraw the bonds it had issued to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 Certainly, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  flatly denied any wrongdoing, arguing that as part of the Cabinet under the authoritarian rule of then president Soeharto it ought to obey the president's instruction not to close banks, notably those owned by Soeharto's cronies.  \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which became a politically independent institution in May 1999, even threatened in 2001 to take back all bank loans and assets (collaterals) from closed and nationalized banks that it had transferred to the government through the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA).  \par \par \uc2 The final resolution should indeed be welcomed as it would theoretically reduce the interest burden of government debts to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  from almost Rp 5 trillion annually to a mere Rp 144.5 billion, and would reschedule the bond maturity to 30 years. The previous bonds begin maturing this year.  \par \par \uc2 The caveat, however, is that the final agreement is tied to the condition that the government pays the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  any shortfall, if \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's capital adequacy ratio (CAR) falls below 3 percent of its total monetary liabilities. But if the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's CAR exceeds 10 percent, it is obliged to transfer the surplus to the government as payments to retire the bonds.  \par \par \uc2 The government's payment obligations to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will therefore fluctuate, depending on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, rupiah rate, inflation and interest rate level, which are all the most influential factors to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's financial performance.  \par \par \uc2 Moreover, the 3 percent CAR threshold that is tied to the agreement will require amendments to the 1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  act as it doesn't specifically mention any CAR ratio. The law stipulates that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's capital shall amount minimally to Rp 2 trillion and that the government is obliged to pay the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  any shortfall (if its capital falls below that amount).  \par \par \uc2 The final agreement, which was based on a political consensus with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  early last month, reflected the government's endorsement of the validity of the credits, with disregard to the Supreme Audit Agency's findings.  \par \par \uc2 Beyond any doubt, the protracted dispute should be resolved. Waiting for further verification of the bad loans and distressed assets transferred by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to IBRA would be rather an impossible mission, because many of the assets have been sold.  \par \par \uc2 The resolution of the dispute is vital to remove once and for all the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the governments \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  balance sheet and is crucial to enable the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to obtain unqualified opinions from the Supreme Audit Agency for its annual financial reports.  \par \par \uc2 However, the agreement is justified only if it is limited to the financial relations between the government and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Because, whatever the formula of the burden sharing might be, the taxpayers will always end up as the biggest losers as losses will simply be transferred from one account of the state to another. After all, despite its independent status, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still owned by the government. Any losses booked to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will simply reduce the amount of profits (surplus) \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be able to remit to the government in the future.  \par \par \uc2 That means that the legal aspects of the auditors' findings about alleged misappropriations and misuse of the liquidity credits should further be investigated. The core issue here is justice.  \par \par \uc2 The Supreme Audit Agency said it had submitted to the Attorney General's Office 50 Bank Indonesian officials implicated in credit misappropriation, but only three of them have so far been brought to court. Several former bank directors and owners found responsible for misusing credits have also been prosecuted.  \par \par \uc2 But the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  believes there are still many more senior officials and former bankers implicated in the loan scam that remain untouched by the justice system. It is these culprits that should be hunted down and brought to justice.  \par \par \uc2 Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020030812dz8d0006f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
