\par\par \b \uc2 BI says continuing post-IMF reforms crucial for  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2 .  \b0\par\par\uc2 593 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 September 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Rendi A. Witular, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) governor Burhanuddin Abdullah said on Monday that pressing ahead with the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program was crucial to maintaining the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery next year.  \par \par \uc2 "There will be possible turbulence next year, but it can be cushioned if the government manages to implement all the post-IMF \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs in a disciplined way," Burhanuddin told businessmen during a gathering with the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin).  \par \par \uc2 He said that pushing ahead with reform programs was crucial to maintaining investor confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly when the existing International Monetary Fund (IMF) \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  bailout program ended later this year, and before general elections next year.  \par \par \uc2 The government has decided not to extend the current IMF program, but opted for a post-program monitoring arrangement (PPM), under which the government will still hold regular consultations with the Fund. However, the government can design in owns reform program. Under the PPM arrangement, Indonesia would not need to repay its loans to the IMF far ahead of installment schedules.  \par \par \uc2 Burhanuddin applauded the government's decision on this, saying that it would allow the country to maintain a high foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  level at a time of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  both at home and in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 One of the immediate impacts of exiting the IMF program is that Indonesia would no longer be eligible for a debt rescheduling facility from the Paris Club of creditor nations, thus creating pressure on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 Burhanuddin said that because of the impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions, it was more crucial for the government to maintain investor confidence.  \par \par \uc2 During the meeting, the governor also urged banks to lower lending rates to make loans more affordable to the corporate sector, which in turn would help push \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth faster.  \par \par \uc2 The government has projected the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow at around 4 percent to 4.5 percent next year, from an average of 3.5 percent during the past couple of years.  \par \par \uc2 "Based on our calculations, if we want to reach the growth target next year, bank loans should grow by 20 to 22 percent," Burhanuddin said  \par \par \uc2 Box  \par \par \uc2 Kadin to invite foreign advisors  \par \par \uc2 The Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) has revealed that it would invite foreign-based financial advisors to establish a joint-monitoring team to supervise the implementation of the government's post-IMF \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform programs as part of efforts to increase pressure when dealing with perilous policies.  \par \par \uc2 Kadin deputy chairman Hariyadi B. Sukamdani said the move was taken after the business lobby met with several foreign ambassadors from the country's traditional donor nations last week.  \par \par \uc2 He said that during the meeting, the donor countries wanted their private sector to be included in the planned monitoring team set up by Kadin.  \par \par \uc2 "We want the government to follow up our concerns. Therefore, it is likely that we will cooperate with the private sector from the donor countries in order to create political pressure on the government," Hariyadi said.  \par \par \uc2 Elsewhere, Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo) chairman Sofjan Wanandi said the request from the ambassadors was a sign of doubt of the government's commitment to applying the post-IMF program.  \par \par \uc2 "There is a distrust toward the Indonesian government. That's why they wanted to be involved in our team," said Sofjan.  \par \par \uc2 The donor countries grouped under the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) comprise, among others, the United States, Japan, Britain, Australia, Canada, France, Germany and Italy.  \par \par \uc2 Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020030915dz9g00012\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
