\par\par \b \uc2 What do analysts, business say about government's post-IMF program?   \b0\par\par\uc2 1,130 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 September 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The White Paper on the government's post-IMF program, which sets out the guidelines to be followed by the government in its bid to secure the recovery of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  once the existing IMF bailout program ends later this year, draws praise and concern from analysts and businesspeople. The following are the comments compiled by The Jakarta Post's Fitri Wulandari.   \par \par \uc2 Fauzi Ichsan, chief economist of Standard Chartered \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2 In general, the programs in the White Paper are market-friendly. They can certainly boost the confidence of international donors and investors.   \par \par \uc2 I think the markets, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and other international donors are very happy at the programs.   \par \par \uc2 However, in my view, the programs are too broad and ambitious in comparison with the IMF letters of intent (LoIs). They cover everything from electricity to transportation to monetary affairs. The LoIs were more focused on and limited to specific issues.   \par \par \uc2 In addition, it lacks a real action plan. Many programs are focused on creating rules of the game but not addressing actual problems.   \par \par \uc2 With such broad programs, it will be difficult for the government to carry them out. The government found it hard to implement even the IMF program, which was more simple than the White Paper. It will be more difficult to implement the programs in view of the tight schedule and the general election next year, on which all attention will be focused.   \par \par \uc2 There are two points that concern market players.   \par \par \uc2 First, the programs lack a disciplinary mechanism. Under the IMF LOIs, if the government failed to carry out a program, the IMF would apply sanctions or penalties, such as delaying the disbursement of loan tranches.   \par \par \uc2 In the White Paper, however, there is no disciplinary measure to be applied if the government fails to implement programs.   \par \par \uc2 For investors, there is no guarantee that the programs will be carried out as scheduled. Who knows, the government might drag its feet in implementing the programs.   \par \par \uc2 Another matter of concern is the lack of real action with regard to politically sensitive issues such as legal action against uncooperative debtors.   \par \par \uc2 Such debtors contributed to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis that pushed the banking industry toward bankruptcy. But the programs did not say if the debtors were going to be tried. The market is very concerned because this lies at the very core of legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the government has still to address it.   \par \par \uc2 Anton Gunawan, chief economist of Citibank Group Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 The market is not that anxious anymore about the White Paper, as its publication was delayed for a month. So, when it was finally published, the market responded rather coolly.   \par \par \uc2 Some of the programs, particularly those relating to macroeconomic sustainability and financial restructuring, are worthy of praise. They are very good and have a clear concept and target. They are very detailed, too.   \par \par \uc2 It is important to maintain continuity of macroeconomic stability.   \par \par \uc2 However, many programs, which are aimed at improving investment, exports and creating employment, are very bad and have no clear direction or target. These are programs for the real sector, which are very important for businesses.   \par \par \uc2 I don't know if the government is serious in addressing the problems in investment, trade and manpower.   \par \par \uc2 For example, the programs say that in order to improve trade, the government will draft a trade law. But what is a trade law? What is the purpose of the law? What is the government trying to achieve with the law?.   \par \par \uc2 On manpower, the program says the government will issue a decree for certified training. That would be just rules of the game. It does not have a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that aims to create a system to improve productivity.   \par \par \uc2 Low productivity is the reason why we cannot compete.   \par \par \uc2 The manpower programs do not answer the issue of how to create industrial relations that are mutually beneficial for employers and workers.   \par \par \uc2 Businesspeople will wish to see an workable program rather than a set of guidelines.   \par \par \uc2 Sofjan Wanandi, chairman of the Association of Indonesian Employers Apindo)   \par \par \uc2 Businesspeople generally welcome programs on macroeconomic stability and financial restructuring.   \par \par \uc2 But we are very skeptical about the program to improve investment, exports and manpower. The programs say the government will set up a center for trade and investment, reform the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  regime and so on. This is nothing new.   \par \par \uc2 The programs lack clear targets. We want to see by how much investment and exports will be increased and to what extent the workforce can be absorbed by the market.   \par \par \uc2 If there are clear targets for inflation, exchange rate and growth, why there are no targets for the real sector?.   \par \par \uc2 Businesspeople are very concerned at these issues because without clear targets, we doubt the government will make an all-out attempt to achieve them, particularly in view of the general election next year, which will predictably divert the government's attention.   \par \par \uc2 There are many issues, such as labor, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and smuggling, that have yet to be addressed by the government. Thus, we are very skeptical that there will be significant improvement.   \par \par \uc2 Another issue is the government's plans to produce new \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  and revise the existing to improve the investment and business climate. But the question is, can the government push the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  to do its homework and complete its deliberations of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  needed by business?   \par \par \uc2 In reality much draft \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  or revisions to it are now in limbo because legislators have not done their jobs properly.   \par \par \uc2 The last issue is the disciplinary mechanism. The government will establish a program to monitor implementation of the White Paper, but it is impossible for the government to punish itself in the event of failure to implement the programs.   \par \par \uc2 Therefore, we are going to establish a monitoring team from the private sector, which will comprise economists, representatives from foreign chambers of commerce and industry and individual businesspeople.   \par \par \uc2 Indra Ibrahim, executive director of the Indonesian Textile Association (API)   \par \par \uc2 The White Paper is only a statement or a declaration. It needs to be followed up by real action. Businesspeople await genuine action from the government.   \par \par \uc2 We hope the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can help attract investors back to Indonesia, particularly within the textile industry. It is estimated that the industry needs new investment of US$4 billion to $5 billion to replace old machinery with new.   \par \par \uc2 Without new investment, it is impossible for the textile industry to compete with other countries, as the market prefers cheaper, good-quality products.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia faces a tough challenge in surviving the liberalization of the textile industry, effective in 2005. The country's low competitiveness very much affects the low level of investment.   \par \par \uc2 I hope the White Paper will raise investor confidence in the country.   \par \par \uc2 Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post.    \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020030916dz9h0000u\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
