\par\par \b \uc2 Govt to go all out to attract more FDI.   \b0\par\par\uc2 669 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 September 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \par \uc2 The government is expected to propose a new investment law to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  in December, which would allow foreign investors to put their money in almost all sectors of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a move to help boost inward investment.   \par \par \uc2 Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) chairman Theo Toemion, however, said on Thursday that foreign investors would still be banned from entering the defense industry, small and medium-sized businesses, and sectors related to religion.   \par \par \uc2 "For us, the lifting of the restrictions is crucial for creating competition. Such competition will then benefit the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  through cheaper products," Theo told reporters.   \par \par \uc2 Currently, foreign investors are prohibited from entering certain sectors set out on the so-called negative investment list.   \par \par \uc2 The plan to propose a new investment bill in December is in line with the government's post-IMF \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program as described in the recent White Paper. According to this document, the government will revise the existing negative investment list.   \par \par \uc2 The media sector, including both the electronic and print media, would be among the sectors affected by the move, Theo said.   \par \par \uc2 Currently, foreign ownership of media companies is prohibited.   \par \par \uc2 The new investment law will replace the existing 1967 investment law.   \par \par \uc2 Besides opening up new sectors to investment, Theo also said that the new investment law would contain measures to minimize the obstacles facing foreign investors, such as excessive red tape.   \par \par \uc2 He did not go into detail, however.   \par \par \uc2 The new bill is expected to help boost foreign direct investment (FDI), a crucial element to allow the country push \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth higher beyond the meager growth rate of 3 percent to 4 percent posted over the past couple of years.   \par \par \uc2 The government has been under pressure to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth to pre-crisis levels of between 6 percent and 7 percent to help create more jobs for the millions of unemployed and job seekers entering the market each year.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, one of the main goals of the post-IMF reform program is too boost investment.   \par \par \uc2 Legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , security fears, labor disputes and poorly managed decentralization are among a few of the problems that have put a brake on investment.   \par \par \uc2 Investment approvals have been in decline since the country was hit by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. In 2002, FDI approvals plummeted by 35 percent, while domestic investment approvals dropped by 57 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Before the crisis, investment was one of the country's main \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth engines.   \par \par \uc2 But nowadays it only accounts for less than 15 percent of the growth in the country's gross domestic product (GDP), with consumption contributing more than 75 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Analysts have long called for comprehensive and coordinated action to address the problems, saying that Indonesia has no choice but to attract investment - especially foreign investment - if it wants its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to expand by more than the current modest levels of around 3 percent to 4 percent.   \par \par \uc2 List of businesses closed to non-state investment   \par \par \uc2 1. Marine and fishing sector   \par \par \uc2 1.1. Harvesting/processing of sponges   \par \par \uc2 2. Industrial and trading sector   \par \par \uc2 2.1. The production of chemicals harmful to the environment   \par \par \uc2 2.2. The production of chemicals such as sarin, soman, halon, etc   \par \par \uc2 2.3. The production of armaments and armaments components   \par \par \uc2 2.4. The production of cyclamate and saccharine   \par \par \uc2 2.5. The production of alcoholic drinks   \par \par \uc2 2.6. Casino and gambling facilities   \par \par \uc2 3. Communications sector   \par \par \uc2 3.1. Air traffic systems providers   \par \par \uc2 3.2 Management and operation of radio frequencies   \par \par \uc2 4. Mines and energy sector   \par \par \uc2 4.1. Mining of radioactive minerals   \par \par \uc2 List of businesses closed to foreign investment   \par \par \uc2 1. Forestry and plantation sector   \par \par \uc2 1.1. Germ plasm cultivation   \par \par \uc2 1.2. Concessions for natural forests   \par \par \uc2 1.3. Contractors in the lumbering field   \par \par \uc2 2. Communications sector   \par \par \uc2 2.1. Taxi/bus transportation services   \par \par \uc2 2.2. Small-scale shipping operations   \par \par \uc2 3. Trading sector   \par \par \uc2 3.1. Trading in support services   \par \par \uc2 4. Information sector   \par \par \uc2 4.1. Radio and television, multimedia and print media   \par \par \uc2 4.2. Motion picture production   \par \par \uc2 Copyright 2003 The Jakarta Post.    \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020030925dz9q00012\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
