\par\par \b \uc2 Why we have failed to recover from the crisis   \b0\par\par\uc2 Sri Pamoedjo Rahardjo, Executive Director, Center for the Study of Administration and Management Indonesia, Jakarta   \par \uc2 645 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 October 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 In contrast to other neighboring countries, Indonesia did not set up a special agency to deal with the crisis. The old guards of the New Order \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  became ineffective because the development continuity was disrupted by the contemporary designs of "Habibienomics".   \par \par \uc2 Reforms were delegated to an already overburdened National Development Planning Agency (Bappenas). Yet, implementation of projects remained in the same troubled sectoral structures. Hence loan compliance could not be properly attended to. And without effective \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  support, the government hesitated in implementing hard and unpopular decisions.   \par \par \uc2 The condition worsened, as the IMF began coaching the administration on what to do and what not to do. The start of the political debacle was marked by the closure of 16 commercial banks as a show of impartiality in bank reform.   \par \par \uc2 The invisible hand of the IMF was unnecessarily extended to cancel the proposed currency \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  under the currency board system. While the concept was debatable, the cancellation deepened social distrust.   \par \par \uc2 Contrary to Malaysia, Indonesia unilaterally scaled down or in some cases closed down on-going projects, and even canceled signed contracts creating \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in business practices.   \par \par \uc2 These actions resulted in a negative chain effect of contractions within the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Hence, major industries adopted a wait and see attitude by downsizing production activities, increasing unemployment. Thus nonperforming loans from national banks had significantly increased which in effect resulted in overall bank liquidity problems.   \par \par \uc2 The worsening condition here should be blamed on both the government and the donors. In the early stage of the crisis, both Indonesian and the World Bank economists were quite aware that it was essentially an urban and Java-based crisis.   \par \par \uc2 Had the strategies been directed to prevent the urban Java \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from crumbling, a different picture may have been drawn about Indonesia today. Instead, the government adopted broad reforms and introduced a social safety net to the detriment of its middle class -- resulting in conflicting jargon.   \par \par \uc2 Worst, the concept of the safety net was extended to bail out financial institutions faced with liquidity problems. The idea could have worked if the local \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was not left to contract. The condition worsened because the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  did not apply any monetary control.   \par \par \uc2 The money market was left opened and the currency rate was left afloat. Indonesian money flowed out seeking safe havens and parked outside the country. Singapore was believed to have housed Indonesians' money reaching over US$100 billion!   \par \par \uc2 Without concrete intervention in program continuity, the impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was mediocre at best. Despite evidence of success in pro-poor program activities, without recovery and revival of production in major industry, these pro-poor projects have began to wilt.   \par \par \uc2 Rather than investing in the poorest of the poor, targeting the significant number of educated middle income groups with better entrepreneurial skills can jump-start the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  with direct trickle-down benefits to the poor.   \par \par \uc2 Many of the pro-poor projects today have not achieved institutional continuity. The recent commotion in the agribusiness company PT QSAR suggests the fragility of the grassroots \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , when it is far too detached from macro \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  interventions, especially when affecting the middle income groups.   \par \par \uc2 President Megawati Soekarnoputri has inherited brittle political, social, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals. Unless all political parties stop squabbling and start rebuilding the country, no leader will ever be able to implement decent macro and micro policies for reconstruction.   \par \par \uc2 As a nation, Indonesians should renew their commitment to reconstruct the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  over and above partisan interests. Even the current government's commitment in a \b \highlight22\uc2 economic stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  package may not yield significant results, if the strategies used continue to overlook the importance of the growing middle income groups not only as consumers of goods, but also as employers in the informal sector.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020031013dzaa00024\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
