\par\par \b \uc2 WB water aid may dry up   \b0\par\par\uc2 Muninggar Sri Saraswati, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 608 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 October 2003\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2003 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The World Bank may not disburse the third and last tranche of the Water Resources Sector Adjustment Loan (Watsal), worth US$150 million, to Indonesia if the controversial water resources bill fails to meet a 1999 commitment on water resource \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform.   \par \par \uc2 Guy Alaerts, the bank's senior water resources specialist, said on Tuesday that the bank was confused about developments in the water bill deliberation.   \par \par \uc2 "We must discuss it with the government whether to continue the programs (or not). If there are different thoughts with regards the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the funding may not continue," said Alaerts.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) has put the bill's deliberation on hold, due to strong \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  reactions concerning the privatization of the water sector.   \par \par \uc2 The bill has also triggered debates on whether water was a commodity or a basic human right.   \par \par \uc2 According to Alaerts, the water resources bill was "absolutely not in line with the loan agreement, the on-going projects nor the grant agreement".   \par \par \uc2 "Therefore, the investment would be useless because there may not be interests or benefits," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Confronted with a severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, the government agreed in 1999 to reform the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on water to allow the privatization of the water sector, in exchange for $300 million in loans. The first and second tranches were disbursed in June 1999 and 2001 respectively, totaling US$150 million.   \par \par \uc2 Many analysts and non-governmental organizations have expressed their opposition to the existing draft water resource bill, as it considers water as an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  commodity, which they say threatens people with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over access to safe and affordable water.   \par \par \uc2 The World Bank sponsored a similar program in Bolivia in 1999, but the program has been at the root of frequent protests over access to safe and affordable water.   \par \par \uc2 Alaerts claimed that the bank and other donors had invested some $1 billion for various projects in water resource management reform in Indonesia, including Watsal.   \par \par \uc2 "If the Indonesian government and the House do not want to continue it, it would create problems not only to Indonesia, but also to donors," he warned.   \par \par \uc2 He said the World Bank and other donors had conducted an initial discussion with the government about the issue.   \par \par \uc2 Alaerts rejected allegations that the water resources investments from the bank was a vehicle for multinational water companies to enter the country.   \par \par \uc2 "Some 95 percent of all funding from the World Bank has nothing to do with private companies. We're not interested in helping them ... no benefit," he said. "(The World Bank) only hopes for more equitable management of water resources so people would be assured access to water in the future."   \par \par \uc2 Legislator Amri Husni Siregar of the Reform faction said the House would not be hasty in deliberating the bill.   \par \par \uc2 "We have no target. We are only concerned about making a \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  that is good and is accepted by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he asserted, adding that the House was scheduled to resume the deliberation later this month.   \par \par \uc2 Amri, who is also a member of the House working committee for the bill's deliberation, said the House would accommodate \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  scrutiny of the bill.   \par \par \uc2 Simon L. Himawan, director of water resources and irrigation with the National Development Planning Board (Bappenas), said the issue had become the government's concern.   \par \par \uc2 "(If they stop the disbursement), Minister (of Finance) Boediono will have a headache, as it will affect the state's financial balance," he said. He suggested the bank to understand that the deliberation was beyond the government's authority, as it was in the hands of the House.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020031014dzaf000b6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
